right;\"  | 14\n|-\n| [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 126\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 24\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 5\n|-\n| [[Taguig]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 95\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n|-\n| [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 21\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 1,380\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 170\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 84\n|-\n|}\n* January 30 \u2013 The Philippines confirmed its first case of coronavirus in Metro Manila and the entire country after a 38-year-old woman from [[Wuhan]] tested positive for COVID-19. She was hospitalized at [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]].<ref name=\"abs1\"/>\n* February 2 \u2013 The first coronavirus-related death outside China was recorded in Manila. A 44-year-old Chinese man died while being treated at the San Lazaro Hospital.<ref name=\"gma1\"/>\n* March 6 \u2013 The first case of community transmission was reported by the DOH, a 62-year-old Filipino man from nearby [[Cainta]] with no known history of travel abroad and who regularly visited a Muslim prayer hall in [[Greenhills (mixed-use development)|Greenhills]], San Juan.\n* March 9 \u2013 The local governments of San Juan, [[Marikina]], and [[Pasay]] ordered the suspension of classes for all levels amid the announcement of the first case of community transmission in the metropolis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/09/1999216/san-juan-marikina-pasay-suspend-classes-over-covid-19 |title=San Juan, Marikina, Pasay suspend classes over COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Servallos, N.J. |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 10\n** President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] ordered the closure of all schools, colleges, and universities in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253912-walang-pasok-duterte-declares-class-suspensions-metro-manila-coronavirus-threat-march-10-14-2020 |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila March 10\u201314 over coronavirus threat |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority#Metro Manila Council|Metro Manila Council]] headed by chairman [[Danilo Lim]] convened to discuss measures to prevent the spread of the virus as confirmed cases in the region climbed to 33.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/photo/03/10/20/metro-mayors-meet-on-local-lockdowns-after-coronavirus-cases-rise |title=Metro mayors meet on local lockdowns after coronavirus cases rise |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Cellona, J. |date=10 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Marikina Mayor [[Marcelino Teodoro]] announced the cancellation of the [[2020 Palarong Pambansa]] as host city of the games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/03/10/marikina-calls-off-palaro/ |title=Marikina calls off Palaro |publisher=[[BusinessMirror]] |author=Bonilla, R.R.C. |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 11 \u2013 Manila Mayor [[Isko Moreno]] went into self-quarantine and isolated himself in the [[Manila City Hall]] after arriving from an official trip to [[London]], U.K.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254164-isko-moreno-self-quarantines-manila-city-hall |title=Isko Moreno self-quarantines at Manila city hall |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Talabong, R. |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 12\n** President Duterte announced a partial lockdown on Metro Manila, placing the entire Metro Manila under community quarantine for thirty days beginning on March 15. The suspension of classes in all levels in Metro Manila was extended to April 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000353/walang-pasok-duterte-suspends-metro-manila-classes-until-april-12 |title=Walang Pasok: Duterte suspends Metro Manila classes until April 12 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Patag, K.J. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** Incidents of [[panic buying]] have been reported across the region triggered by the president's partial lockdown order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240902/look-panic-buying-amid-lockdown-fears-in-metro |title=LOOK: Panic-buying amid lockdown fears in Metro Manila |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Marquez, C. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 13\n** The local chief executives of [[Caloocan]], [[Malabon]], [[Navotas]], and [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]: [[Oscar Malapitan]], [[Antolin Oreta]], [[Toby Tiangco]], and [[Rex Gatchalian]], respectively, went into self-quarantine after learning they had come into contact with a confirmed coronavirus patient at a March 5 event in Caloocan's [[North Luzon Expressway]]\u2013Harbor Link.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240982/camanava-mayors-under-quarantine |title=Camanava mayors under quarantine |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Adonis, M. |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Manila]] suspended all worship services and activities in their parishes across Metro Manila for seven days beginning March 14. The [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cubao|Diocese of Cubao]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Novaliches|Diocese of Novaliches]], and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Para\u00f1aque|Diocese of Para\u00f1aque]] have also issued a similar directive for their parishioners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254346-manila-churches-suspend-masses-coronavirus-lockdown |title=Manila churches suspend Masses amid coronavirus lockdown |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Esmaquel, P. |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n**The MMDA announced a postponement of the 1st [[Metro Manila Summer Film Festival]] as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/13/20/summer-mmff-postponed-after-metro-manila-put-under-community-quarantine |title=Summer MMFF postponed after Metro Manila put under 'community quarantine' |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n** The DOH reported that four COVID-19 patients in the region had died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/qc-state-of-calamity.html |title=Quezon City declares state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=CNN PH staff |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 14\n** The [[University Athletic Association of the Philippines]] cancelled [[UAAP Season 82]] games and all other collegiate and high school tournaments in Metro Manila from March 15 to April 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/sports/content/729693/uaap-cancels-season-82-hs-tourneys-current-format-collegiate-matches-amid-covid-19-scare/story/ |title=UAAP cancels Season 82 HS tourneys, current format collegiate matches amid COVID-19 scare |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Santos, J. |date=March 14, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** A mass exodus to the provinces was observed in the hours leading to the Metro Manila lockdown. Thousands were seen flocking to the provincial bus terminals such as the [[Araneta City Bus Port]] in Quezon City as well as the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254503-photos-mass-exodus-metro-manila-lockdown-coronavirus |title=IN PHOTOS: Mass exodus before Metro Manila 'lockdown' |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Rey, A. |date=March 14, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 15\n** A total of 56 checkpoints were set up in numerous points of entry to Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1242619/police-seal-metro-manila-to-fight-virus |title=Police seal Metro Manila to fight virus |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Yamsuan, C.C., Agoncillo, J.A. |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n**Following a directive from the Metro Manila Council and the confirmation of COVID-19 cases, the city mayors of Makati, Manila, Pasig, and San Juan declare a [[State of emergency|state of calamity]].<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n** Shopping mall chains [[Ayala Malls]] and [[SM Supermalls]] announced the temporary closure of all their establishments across Metro Manila. [[Robinsons Metro East]], [[Power Plant Mall]], and Greenhills have also closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/lifestyle/shoppingandfashion/729778/metro-manila-malls-to-temporarily-close-amid-covid-19-threat/story/ |title=Metro Manila malls to temporarily close amid COVID-19 threat |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Cabuenas, J.V.D. |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Philippine Amusement and Gaming Corporation]] ordered the suspension of all gaming operations in Metro Manila, including the land-based casinos in [[Entertainment City]] and [[Newport City, Metro Manila|Newport City]]. The gaming regulator also announced that they were limiting the operations of [[Philippine offshore gaming operation]]s in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/15/20/pagcor-suspends-casino-gaming-operations-during-metro-manila-quarantine |title=PAGCOR suspends casino, gaming operations during Metro Manila quarantine |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n**Motorcycle ride-sharing companies [[Angkas]] and Joyride suspended their Metro Manila services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/15/angkas-joyride-suspend-operations-in-metro-manila-but-deliveries-continue/ |title=Angkas, Joyride suspend operations in Metro Manila, but deliveries continue |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |author=Ramos, M. |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n* March 16\n** President Duterte [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|imposed an \"enhanced\" community quarantine]] covering the entire [[Luzon]], including Metro Manila, suspending [[Transportation in the Philippines|mass public transportation]]; restricting land, air, and sea travel; imposing strict home quarantine; and closing most private establishments until April 13.<ref name=\"gazette1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-community-quarantine-over-the-entire-luzon-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Community Quarantine Over the Entire Luzon and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation|date=March 16, 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**The [[National Commission on Muslim Filipinos]] announced a temporary suspension of all Islamic gatherings in the region in response to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001412/islamic-religious-activities-metro-manila-other-areas-under-covid-19-quarantine-temporarily-suspended |title=Islamic religious activities in Metro Manila, other areas under COVID-19 quarantine temporarily suspended |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Cabico, G.K. |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n*March 17\n**The Manila bourse became the first major market in the world to shut down over coronavirus fears. It suspended trading for two days following a [[2020 stock market crash|global stock market crash]] which saw the main [[Philippine Stock Exchange]] index plunge more than 30 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/philippines-shuts-financial-markets-after-virus-spurs-stock-rout |title=Philippines Becomes First Country to Shut Financial Markets Thanks to Virus |publisher=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |author1=Tu, Lianting |author2=Sayson, Ian C. |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n**Hundreds of commuters were left stranded as public transport came to a halt due to the government-imposed partial lockdown. Traffic jams were also reported at border checkpoints.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729980/enhanced-quarantine-strands-hundreds-at-checkpoints/story/ |title=Enhanced Luzon quarantine strands hundreds at checkpoints |publisher=[[GMA Network]] |author=Rita, J. |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The Archdiocese of Manila extended the suspension of public masses to April 14 and announced the suspension of all [[Holy Week]] activities set for April in all parishes in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/bishops-suspend-holy-week-activities-in-metro-manila/ |title=Bishops suspend Holy Week activities in Metro Manila |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |author=[[Philippine News Agency]] |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n**Food delivery services [[Grab (company)|GrabFood]] and [[Foodpanda]] resumed operations in the region after a temporary suspension due to quarantine restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/business/2020/3/17/Grab-Philippines-car-GrabFood-suspended-coronavirus.html |title=GrabFood, FoodPanda resume food delivery services amid Luzon quarantine |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*March 18 \u2013 Vice President [[Leni Robredo]] announced the roll out of a free shuttle service for medical personnel working in the front lines of the pandemic in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244079/ovps-shuttle-service-for-metro-manila-covid-19-medical-frontliners-starts-run |title=OVP\u2019s shuttle service for Metro Manila COVID-19 medical frontliners starts run |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Gonzales, C. |date=March 18, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n*March 20 \u2013 The Health department has designated the [[Philippine General Hospital]] in [[Ermita]] and [[Dr. Jose N. Rodriguez Memorial Hospital]] in [[Caloocan]] as national COVID-19 referral hospitals in Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/20/Lung-Center-Jose-Rodriguez-Memorial-Caloocan-COVID-exclusive-hospitals-DOH.html |title=Memorial designated as exclusive COVID-19 hospitals \u2013 Health dept. |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author1=Bonquin, C. |author2=Rola, A. |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*March 24 \u2013 [[Makati Medical Center]], [[The Medical City]], De Los Santos Medical Center, [[St. Luke's Medical Center|St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Quezon City]] and [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Global City]] reported operating at full-capacity due to the pandemic and urged patients to look for alternative hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247913/5-metro-hospitals-reach-full-capacity-for-covid-19-cases |title=5 Metro Manila hospitals reach full capacity for COVID-19 cases |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yamsuan, C.C. |author2=Yee, J. |date=March 25, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n*March 25 \u2013 The national government announced a cash aid for poor families affected by the pandemic in the region amounting to {{Philippine peso|8,000}} of monthly subsidy over two months as part of the {{Philippine peso|200 billion}} cash assistance program under the ''[[Bayanihan to Heal as One Act]]'' signed by President Duterte.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1252020/cash-aid-for-poor-p-8000-in-metro-p-5000-in-regions |title=Cash aid for poor: P8,000 in Metro; P5,000 in regions |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yap, DJ |author2=Yee, J. |author3=Salaverria, L.B. |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n*March 26 \u2013 The [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]] launched its first mobile [[farmers' market]] in the region, the ''Kadiwa on Wheels'', in [[Quezon City]], to ensure enough food supply amid the closure of most retail establishments due to the region-wide quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.untvweb.com/news/farm-products-at-cheaper-price-available-at-kadiwa-on-wheels-da/ |title=Farm products at cheaper price available at \u2018Kadiwa on Wheels\u2019 \u2014 DA |publisher=[[UNTV (Philippines)]] |author=Pelayo, M. |date=26 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*March 28\n**The [[Manila International Airport Authority]] announced the temporary closure of all terminals of the Manila-Ninoy Aquino except [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport Terminal 1|Terminal 1]] following the suspension of domestic flights and international travel restrictions due to the pandemic and subsequent lockdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/28/2003833/airlines-mount-cargo-only-flights-transport-vital-goods |title=Airlines mount \u2018cargo-only\u2019 flights to transport vital goods |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Mercurio, R. |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] General Manager Jojo Garcia was confirmed as coronavirus positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/28/2003984/mmda-general-manager-positive-covid-19 |title=MMDA general manager positive for COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=San Juan, R. |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*March 29 \u2013 A total of 370 repatriated [[overseas Filipino worker]]s from three cruise ships in [[Italy]], a country severely affected by the global outbreak, arrived at Manila's [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250394/370-filipinos-from-3-docked-cruise-ships-in-italy-arrive-in-manila |title=370 Filipinos from 3 cruise ships docked in Italy arrive in Manila |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Hallare, K. |date=29 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*March 30 \u2013 Severe congestion at the [[Port of Manila]] was reported two weeks after the region was placed under lockdown with many unclaimed food cargoes and overstaying containers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/business/256372-ictsi-says-food-cargo-stuck-manila-port-coronavirus-lockdown |title=Food cargo stuck at Manila port due to coronavirus lockdown \u2013 ICTSI |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Rivas, R. |date=30 March 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*April 1\n**Twenty-one protesters at a rally in [[Quezon City]] demanding food and aid were arrested for violating the enhanced community quarantine protocols.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/1/quezon-city-protesters-arrested-.html |title=21 protesters demanding food aid arrested in Quezon City |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n**The local government of Manila reported its largest single-day increase in coronavirus infections so far with 41 new cases, bringing the city's total to 116.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/1/manila-records-largest-single-day-jump-coronavirus-.html |title=City of Manila records largest single-day jump in COVID-19\u00a0cases, total now at 116 |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n**GrabWheels, an [[electric scooter]] rental service of [[Grab (company)|Grab]], was activated to service health workers in select cities in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.mb.com.ph/2020/04/01/grabwheels-activated-for-health-workers/ |title=GrabWheels activated for health workers |publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]] |author=Abadilla, E.V. |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 2\n** The Inter-Agency Task Force on Emerging Infectious Diseases (IATF-EID) chairman [[Carlito Galvez Jr.]] announced that Metro Manila remains the epicenter of the coronavirus crisis in the country after 1,511 cases have been confirmed in the region, or more than 50 percent of the total confirmed cases in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/02/20/metro-manila-remains-ph-epicenter-of-coronavirus-crisis-galvez |title=Metro Manila remains PH epicenter of coronavirus crisis - Galvez |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Maru, D. |date=2 April 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n<center>\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=700\n|colors= #39FF14, #87CEEB, #FFDF00, #EF5350, #FE4EDA, #C0C0C0, #FF7E00\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=Jan 30, Feb 1, Feb 2, Feb 5, Mar 13, Mar 16, Mar 17, Mar 19, Mar 24, Mar 25, Mar 26, Mar 27, Mar 28, Mar 29, Mar 30, Mar 31, Apr 1, Apr 2, Apr 3, Apr 4\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases in selected cities\n|legend=Legend\n|y1=0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 15, 14, 18, 20, 31, 31, 33, 33, 33, 45, 45, 47, 144, 158, 158\n|y1Title=Makati\n|y2=0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 5, 6, 7, 16, 20, 22, 31, 35, 39, 39, 50, 60, 73, 78, 89\n|y2Title=Mandaluyong\n|y3=1, 1, 2, 1, 1, 8, 8, 13, 10, 32, 32, 34, 44, 55, 55, 70, 75, 127, 138, 156\n|y3Title=Manila\n|y4=0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 11, 11, 13, 19, 26, 26, 33, 33, 33, 33, 41, 41, 41, 105, 105\n|y4Title=Pasig\n|y5=0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 24, 26, 34, 62, 72, 87, 97, 104, 113, 113, 140, 151, 174, 188, 336\n|y5Title=Quezon City\n|y6=0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 15, 19, 23, 48, 48, 57, 69, 73, 79, 94, 94, 99, 117, 123, 126\n|y6Title=San Juan\n|y7=0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 3, 3, 6, 19, 26, 26, 27, 35, 45, 45, 55, 62, 78, 83, 95\n|y7Title=Taguig\n\n|yGrid= |xGrid= \n}}\n</cente