Bulacan]] in [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]], March 19, 2020]]\nBefore the partial lockdown on Metro Manila declared on March 12, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] had initially suspended classes across all levels in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14 upon reaching a consensus with the [[Metro Manila Council]] (the mayors of Metro Manila) due to the rapidly increasing number of cases especially in the area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=Virgil |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14, 2020 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/serbisyopubliko/walangpasok/728993/duterte-suspends-classes-in-metro-manila-from-march-10-to-14-2020/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, President Duterte announced a partial lockdown covering Metro Manila, that begun on March 15 and will last until April 14. Under the partial lockdown:<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Ana |title=Ghost town: Manila under coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/manila-turns-ghost-town-coronavirus-lockdown-200315121507679.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* The region is closed to land, air, and sea travel. However, mass transportation within Metro Manila such as the [[Manila Light Rail Transit System|Manila LRT]] and [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System|MRT]] continues to operate under proper [[social distancing]] guidelines.\n* Suspension of classes at all levels in Metro Manila is extended until April 14.\n* Spontaneous and planned mass gatherings are banned.\n* Work in the Executive department is suspended under the lockdown period.\n* The [[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|Department of Labor and Employment]] encourages employers in the private sector to arrange \"flexible work arrangements\".\n\nFollowing the declaration of the partial lockdown, the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] (MMDA) suspended the enforcement of the [[Unified Vehicular Volume Reduction Program]], more commonly known as the number coding scheme.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Jel |title=Number coding suspended indefinitely due to 'community quarantine' \u2014 MMDA |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/13/number-coding-suspended-indefinitely-due-to-community-quarantine-mmda/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On the eve of the Metro Manila lockdown, the MMDA announced the imposition of an area-wide [[curfew]] from 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. the following day to be observed during the lockdown, during which only \"essential movements\" for the purchase of essential needs or in cases of emergency are permitted during those hours.<ref>{{cite news |title=Curfew from 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. to take effect in Metro Manila under COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/14/20/metro-manila-quarantine-curfew |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The Metro Manila Council unanimously approved the imposition of the curfew in a joint resolution. All local governments, except for [[Marikina]] and [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]], had adopted ordinances imposing the curfew in their respective cities, effective by March 20.<ref>{{cite news |title=LIST: Metro Manila cities with COVID-19 curfew |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/Metro-Manila-COVID-19-curfew-list.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In that joint resolution, the council also ordered the closure of shopping malls and other establishments during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cordero |first1=Ted |title=Metro Manila Council wants malls temporarily closed amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729652/metro-manila-council-wants-malls-temporarily-closed-amid-covid-19-threat/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA total of 56 checkpoints were set up to man the borders of Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\"/> At 12 midnight, a total of 26,000 police and military personnel were deployed to contain the pandemic of COVID-19 in the region. Motorists were stopped randomly and asked for their identification along the borders in North Luzon Expressway, [[MacArthur Highway]], and the National Road ([[Maharlika Highway]]). Some checkpoints lacked thermal scanners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254565-metro-manila-lockdown-implementation-checkpoints-march-15-2020 |title=Day 1 of Metro Manila lockdown: Different checkpoints, different rules |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Cupin, B., Rivas, R. & Tomacruz, S. |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite the moratorium on mass public transportation during the \"enhanced\" community quarantine, Vice President [[Leni Robredo]] launched free shuttle bus services for those individuals exempted from the quarantine, specifically health professionals, front line government officials, and essential service providers. Robredo's shuttle services travel five routes around Metro Manila, connecting the major hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Robredo donates gear to health workers, pledges free shuttle rides |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/robredo-donation-health-workers.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Some city governments also deployed such transportation services.\n\nTo address concerns regarding the hoarding and [[panic buying]] of essential goods, some city governments issued ordinances to limit the amount of such goods an individual or establishment could purchase.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa declares state of calamity due to COVID-19 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/muntinlupa-declares-state-of-calamity-due-to-covid-19/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Pasig anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=Pasig City OKs anti-hoarding, panic buying ordinance |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243408/pasig-city-anti-panic-buying-ordinance-story |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Valenzuela anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=David |first1=Jun |title=Valenzuela passes anti-hoarding, anti-panic buying measure |url=https://manilastandard.net/index.php/lgu/ncr/319768/valenzuela-passes-anti-hoarding-anti-panic-buying-measure.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Manila Standard |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] has on March 20, 2020 has announced that it has designated three health facilities as COVID-19 referral hospitals namely the [[Philippine General Hospital|UP-Philippine General Hospital]] (UP-PGH) in Manila, the Dr. Jose M. Rodriguez Memorial Hospital and Sanitarium in Caloocan and the [[Lung Center of the Philippines]] in Quezon City. The UP-PGH has stopped admitting non-emergency cases and the Lung Center has dedicated one of its wings of 40 beds for COVID-19 patients. The Philippine Blood Center likewise will not admit any suspected COVID-19 cases with the health department encouraging the public to continue donate blood for COVID-19 patients with critical and severe conditions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galvez |first1=Daphne |title=PGH, 2 other institutions chosen as COVID-19 referral hospitals |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245731/covid-19-referral-hospitals |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVice President Robredo converted a [[dormitory]] in [[Quezon City#Cubao|Cubao, Quezon City]], to provide free accommodations for front line health professionals during the \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=Robredo launches free dormitory in QC for COVID-19 frontliners |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248747/robredo-launches-free-dormitory-in-qc-for-covid-19-frontliners |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVarious facilities in the metropolis are being prepared as quarantine sites for less serious COVID-19 cases. Among these are the [[Philippine International Convention Center]], the [[Rizal Memorial Sports Complex]], and the [[World Trade Center Manila|World Trade Center]] will be fully refurbish by April 12. The three facilities alone can accommodate around 2,000 COVID-19 patients. Other non-hospital facilities being considered as possible quarantine sites include the [[PhilSports Complex]], Duty Free Philippines in Para\u00f1aque, [[Amoranto Stadium]], and the [[Quezon Memorial Circle]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Three COVID-19 quarantine facilities in Metro Manila ready by April 12 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/2/Metro-Manila-quarantine-facility-COVID-19.html |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Local governments ===\n==== Caloocan ====\n[[Caloocan]] Mayor [[Oscar Malapitan]] announced on March 10 the suspension of several scheduled events, namely the Miss Caloocan Pageant, Mega Job Fairs, City Development Council General Assembly, Outstanding Citizens Awards Night, and Family Day activities, to prevent the spread of the virus amongst large crowds.<ref name=\"Caloocan, Valenzuela\">{{cite news |last1=Caybyab |first1=Marc Jayson |title=Caloocan, Valenzuela cancel events over COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/10/1999490/caloocan-valenzuela-cancel-events-over-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> On March 15, the Caloocan city council passed an ordinance imposing the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Caloocan to strictly implement 8 pm-to-5 am curfew |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/16/caloocan-to-strictly-implement-8-pm-to-5-am-curfew/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Malapitan announced on March 24 that the city government would impose window hours on residents for the purchase of essential goods. Residents could only access the city's [[Palengke|public markets]] between 6{{nbsp}}a.m. to 9{{nbsp}}a.m. and 4{{nbsp}}p.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m., while supermarkets, banks, and pharmacies can only be accessed between 6{{nbsp}}a.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m. The city would also issue quarantine passes, permitting only one resident per household between the ages of 18 to 60 years old to leave their house solely for purchasing such goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Caloocan gov\u2019t imposes window hours for buying basic goods |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247566/caloocan-govt-imposes-window-hours-for-buying-basic-goods |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Las Pi\u00f1as ====\n[[Las Pi\u00f1as]] Mayor Imelda Aguilar declared a state of calamity in the city on March 14 after a resident was confirmed to have tested positive for COVID-19<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as declares state of calamity amid coronavirus alarm |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/14/20/las-pias-declares-state-of-calamity-amid-coronavirus-alarm |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> and on March 21, the Las Pi\u00f1as government began implementing a 24-hour curfew on its residents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Las Pi\u00f1as City imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/las-pinas-city-imposes-24-hour-curfew/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Makati ====\nIn response to the confirmation of residents of the [[Rockwell Center]] contracting COVID-19, [[Makati]] Mayor [[Abigail Binay]] placed the city under a state of calamity on March 15.<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n\nOn March 17, the Makati government launched free shuttle bus services for doctors, nurses, and other employees of the Ospital ng Makati, which runs between the hospital and certain points in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Makati gov't deploys buses for OsMak, city hall employees |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243764/makati-govt-deploys-buses-for-osmak-city-hall-employees |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> In addition, Mayor Binay announced that tricycle drivers affected by the moratorium would receive an initial {{Philippine peso|2,000|link=yes}} (US$39.23) financial assistance to cover the first two weeks of the quarantine. Binay added that a similar financial compensation would be given to jeepney drivers of the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Makati to give P2,000-financial aid to city's tricycle drivers |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244295/makati-to-give-p2000-to-citys-tricycle-drivers-as-financial-aid |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Makati Friendship Suites on March 25 was converted into an [[Isolation (health care)|isolation facility]] by the city government to accommodate at most 100 patients suspected of COVID-19 and is equipped with [[x-ray machine]]s, [[defibrillator]]s, and [[cardiac monitor]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Layug |first1=Margaret Claire |title=Makati converts hotel into isolation facility for COVID-19 PUIs |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731239/makati-converts-hotel-into-isolation-facility-for-covid-19-puis/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Malabon ====\nOn March 16, the [[Malabon]] city council approved an ordinance imposing the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |title=Malabon approves 8 pm to 5 am curfew starting March 16 |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254723-malabon-curfew-coronavirus |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, Malabon Mayor [[Antolin Oreta]] ordered the city government to provide {{Philippine peso|520,000}} ($10,252.26) to each ''barangay'' for the provision of food during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. Oreta also ordered the provision of {{Philippine peso|6 million}} ($118,156.44) to the city's ''carinderia'' (food stall) owners for them to provide meals for 300 people every day for 15 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Malabon City gov\u2019t releases food budget to barangays for needy residents |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/malabon-city-govt-releases-food-budget-to-barangays-for-needy-residents/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> That same day, he called on [[Maynilad Water Services]] to divert the unused [[Water supply and sanitation in the Philippines|water supply]] of closed malls and other commercial establishments to residential areas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Malabon mayor asks water concessionaires to divert mall water supply to residential areas amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/malabon-mayor-asks-water-concessionaires-to-divert-mall-water-supply-to-residential-areas-amid-covid-19-threat/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Mandaluyong ====\nOn March 16, the [[Mandaluyong]] city council passed an ordinance declaring the city under a state of calamity, after reporting three COVID-19 patients, six persons under investigation, and 125 persons under monitoring in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong declares state of calamity over spread of COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/mandaluyong-declares-state-of-calamity-over-spread-of-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Mandaluyong Mayor [[Carmelita Abalos]] ordered the release of the [[thirteenth salary]] pay to all of the city's government employees.<ref name=\"13th-month pay\">{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong, Manila gov't employees to get early 13th-month, midyear pay during community quarantine |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/mandaluyong-city-hall-13th-month.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Manila ====\n[[File:Philippine General Hospital COVID-19 ward.jpg|thumb|A ward dedicated to COVID-19 patients at the [[Philippine General Hospital]] in [[Ermita]], [[Manila]], March 28, 2020]]\n\n[[Manila]] Mayor [[Isko Moreno]], following a directive from the Metro Manila Council, declared a state of calamity in the city on March 15 after the second and third COVID-19 cases were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254621-manila-state-calamity-new-confirmed-coronavirus-cases |title=Manila under state of calamity as city confirms 2 new coronavirus\u00a0cases |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Modular Tent Home for Street Dwellers Manila COVID19 1.jpg|thumb|right|A gymnasium in [[Manila]] converted into a temporary homeless shelter during the region-wide community quarantine]]\nThe Manila Department of Social Welfare (MDSW) on March 16 began rescuing [[street people]], [[pavement dwellers]], and other homeless people, as well as people living outside the city who were unable to retreat home following the imposition of the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. They took refuge at the Delpan Sports Complex in [[Tondo, Manila|Tondo]]. Mayor Isko Moreno allocated {{Philippine peso|227.5 million}} ($4.45 million) from the city's budget to assist families affected by the quarantine. MDSW Chief Re Fugoso ordered the lockdown of the Manila Boys Town Complex and the Manila Youth Reception Center in [[Ermita]] for the protection of the children and teenagers residing there amid the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tiangco |first1=Minka |title=Street dwellers given food, shelter by Manila City government |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/street-dwellers-given-food-shelter-by-manila-city-government/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Likewise Mayor Moreno on March 18 ordered all lodging facilities in Manila to provide free accommodations for front line health workers, such as doctors and nurses, throughout the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Talabong |first1=Rambo |title=Isko Moreno orders Manila hotels, motels to house health workers for free |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255062-isko-moreno-order-hotels-motels-manila-house-health-workers-for-free |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Manila government on March 19 deployed 189 [[Electric bicycle#Tricycles|electric tricycles]] to exclusively transport front line health workers to the city's public hospitals. Non-health workers would not be serviced in observance of the moratorium on mass public transportation; however, drivers of electric tricycles would receive salaries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=Manila to deploy 189 e-trikes for COVID-19 frontliners |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730444/manila-to-deploy-189-e-trikes-for-covid-19-frontliners/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Moreno on March 17 drafted a resolution ordering the release of the mid-year bonuses of the city's government employees. He also drafted another resolution appropriating funds for the city's job order and [[Endo contractualization|contractualized workers]].<ref name=\"13th-month pay\"/>\n\nThe Manila government on March 25 also coordinated with the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development]] of the national government in sourcing food supplies for the city's families. Mayor Moreno has stressed that the Manila government could only produce between 8,000 and 11,000 food packs, but would not suffice for the city's 350,000 families. The city government had already provided for about 39,000 families.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Merez |first1=Arianne |title=Isko Moreno appeals for food supplies for Manila |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/25/20/isko-moreno-appeals-for-food-supplies-for-manila |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Mayor Isko Moreno launched an [[Survey data collection#Online survey|online survey]] via his [[Facebook]] page inquiring Manila residents about their health status in relation to COVID-19 and their recent travel history. [[PLDT]], one of the country's major telecommunications providers, assisted the city government in providing enhanced data connectivity for the online survey service. PLDT also assisted in augmenting the hotline facility at the [[Manila City Hall]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hilario |first1=Edgard |title=Manila City Hall launches city-wide COVID-19 health survey |url=https://technology.mb.com.ph/2020/03/23/manila-city-hall-launches-city-wide-covid-19-health-survey/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Marikina ====\n[[Marikina]] Mayor [[Marcelino Teodoro]] on March 16 announced that his government would install misting and decontamination tents across numerous public spaces in the city.<ref name=setup>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Marikina City to set up lab testing center for the detection of COVID-19 cases |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/14/marikina-city-to-set-up-lab-testing-center-for-the-detection-of-covid-19-cases/}}</ref> The Marikina government pledged to provide households with free disinfectant solutions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Madarang |first1=Catalina Ricci |title=Marikina City, MMDA step up efforts vs COVID-19 with disinfection tents |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/trends-spotlights/2020/03/16/164301/marikina-mmda-covid19-disinfection-tents/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn light of the moratorium on mass public transportation during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine, the Marikina government launched on March 18 free shuttle bus services to ferry front line health professionals from across the city to its hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ornedo |first1=Julia Mari |title=Marikina adds more routes to free ride service for residents amid quarantine |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730277/marikina-adds-more-routes-to-free-ride-service-for-residents-amid-quarantine/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Marikina government also launched an initiative to set up a COVID-19 testing center. On March 16, Mayor Teodoro announced that around 3,000 testing kits would be procured and that Marikina will assemble a laboratory testing center, in partnership with Manila Health Tek and the [[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|Philippine National Institutes of Health]], to test \"[[Patient Under Investigation|patients under investigation]]\" (PUIs) for COVID-19.<ref name=setup/> Free COVID-19 testing is planned to be provided to health professionals and other suspected cases through the testing center. Field testing was scheduled to begin on March 24. The procurement of a {{Philippine peso|2.7 million}} ($53,222.42) [[polymerase chain reaction]] machine specifically for testing, along with 3,000 test kits worth {{Philippine peso|4 million}} ($78,824.72) was also announced by the city government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Panti |first1=Llanesca |title=Marikina sets up lab, buys equipment to give free COVID-19 tests |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/730475/marikina-to-provide-free-covod-19-testing-to-health-workers-persons-at-risk/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nOn March 26, Mayor Teodoro reported that the DOH rejected the usage of the city government's COVID-19 testing center because of its location, which had to be in a \"separate free-standing building\", but was located inside the Marikina City Health Office. Teodoro claimed that their testing center had met all the other criteria for a testing center and he even offered to cede its full operation to the DOH.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ornedo |first1=Julia Mari |title=DOH rejected COVID-19 testing center, Marikina mayor says |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731398/doh-rejected-covid-19-testing-center-marikina-mayor-says/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> However, the DOH refuted the mayor's claims that they had rejected the usage of the testing center.<ref>{{cite news |title=Health dept denies rejecting Marikina's COVID-19 test lab |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/26/20/health-dept-denies-rejecting-marikinas-covid-19-test-lab |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Nevertheless, Teodoro said that his government would relocate its testing center.<ref name=\"Marikina\">{{cite news |last1=Ayalin |first1=Adrian |title=Marikina to transfer COVID-19 testing center to separate building to comply with DOH requirements |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/27/20/marikina-to-transfer-covid-19-testing-center-to-separate-building-to-comply-with-doh-requirements |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 27, the Marikina government designated the defunct Marikina Hotel to serve as an isolation facility for \"patients under monitoring\" (PUMs) with suspected diagnosis of the virus.<ref name=\"Marikina\"/>\n\n==== Muntinlupa ====\n\nOn March 10, [[Muntinlupa]] Mayor [[Jaime Fresnedi]] organized a COVID-19 task force. He ordered schools and government facilities in the city to be disinfected.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\">{{cite news |author1=[[Ignacio Bunye|Bunye, Ignacio]] |title=Muntinlupa City\u2019s response to coronavirus \u2013 a timeline |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/23/muntinlupa-citys-response-to-coronavirus-a-timeline/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Mayor Fresnedi ordered Muntinlupa ''barangay'' officials to identify residents with recent travel history for monitoring. He also ordered officials to install isolation facilities to accommodate suspected cases of COVID-19; the city government assembled a [[field hospital]] outside the Ospital ng Muntinlupa, which became fully operational on March 18. Police officials were deployed to prevent students from entering malls, following the suspension of classes in Metro Manila.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\"/>\n\nOn March 16, Mayor Fresnedi placed the city under a state of calamity, after confirming its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite web |title=Muntinlupa City Declares State Of Calamity Due To COVID-19 Emergency |url=https://www.muntinlupacity.gov.ph/?p=18062 |publisher=City Government of Muntinlupa |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The Muntinlupa city council approved four ordinances in relation to addressing the pandemic: the first is to prevent the hoarding and panic buying of essential goods; the second is to prohibit the sale, distribution, and consumption of alcoholic beverages during the duration of the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine; the third is to order the closure of all private establishments in the city, except for those providing essential goods such as supermarkets, pharmacies, and banks; and the fourth is to restrict the operation of restaurants, ''carinderias'', and other eateries to [[take-out]] only.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa anti-hoarding\"/> \n\nOn March 17, the Muntinlupa government launched free shuttle services for front line workers based in the city, deploying [[Jeepney#E-jeepneys|electric jeepneys]].<ref name=\"Muntinlupa\"/> \n\nOn March 19, Mayor Fresnedi met with the city's [[Barangay Captain]]s, instructing them to strictly implement and enforce the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew and social distancing measures in accordance with the national government's guidelines. A Barangay Captain also ordered the lockdown of an undisclosed subdivision in [[Alabang]] following confirmation from the DOH that two confirmed COVID-19 cases in the city are residents of that subdivision.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa City gov\u2019t to intensify community quarantine measures |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/19/muntinlupa-city-govt-to-intensify-community-quarantine-measures/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Fresnedi led the distribution of 1,500 food packages in [[Poblacion, Muntinlupa|Poblacion]]. Fresnedi assured the city's residents that the city government will provide food assistance to the city's \"vulnerable households\" that would last for up to three to four months. He also ordered the advanced release of the thirteenth salary pay of the city hall's employees.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa ready to provide food assistance up to 4 months |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/20/muntinlupa-ready-to-provide-food-assistance-up-to-4-months/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, Mayor Fresnedi signed into effect an ordinance passed by the city council to impose a 24-hour city-wide curfew, superseding the 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. curfew.<ref>{{cite news |title=Muntinlupa placed under 24-hour curfew |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/21/muntinlupa-under-24-hour-curfew.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the Muntinlupa city council passed an ordinance to convert the Ospital ng Muntinlupa into a COVID-19 testing facility. The government would procure polymerase chain reaction machines and testing kits. The city already houses the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in Alabang, one of five medical facilities accredited by the DOH to perform COVID-19 testing in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa wants to establish own COVID-19 testing center |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/24/muntinlupa-wants-to-establish-own-covid-19-testing-center/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Navotas ====\n\nPrior to President Duterte's declaration of a partial lockdown on Metro Manila, [[Navotas]] Mayor [[Toby Tiangco]] had already suspended classes at all levels in the city for March 9 as a preventive measure against the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mendoza |first1=Red |title=Navotas suspends classes due to Covid-19 outbreak |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/07/news/latest-stories/navotas-suspends-classes-due-to-covid-19-outbreak/700948/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Tiangco also appealed to the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]] to pass all students in the city for the school year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Navotas mayor asks DepEd to pass all students; Duque says class suspension not a good idea now |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728716/navotas-mayor-asks-deped-to-pass-all-students-duque-says-class-suspension-not-a-good-idea-now/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the Navotas government issued an ordinance limiting the amount of work required for its government officials to work 10 hours per day for four days, effective March 16, in observance of social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navotas to implement 4-day work week for some LGU offices, employees |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/13/20/navotes-4-day-work-week-due-to-covid-19-coronavirus |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the Navotas city council passed an ordinance imposing an 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew from March 16 to April 14, as agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council. It also required commercial establishments, except for those providing essential goods, to close before the start of the curfew.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gavilan |first1=Jodesz |title=Navotas City approves curfew from 8 pm to 5 am |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254632-navotas-city-passes-curfew-ordinance-novel-coronavirus |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, the Navotas government began distributing around 18,000 food packs to the city's [[Slums in Metro Manila|informal settlers]] living in \"danger zones\" and families listed under the city's housing projects.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paunan |first1=Jerome Carlo |title=Navotas uses 'katok' system for family food pack delivery amid quarantine |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036876 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 23, Mayor Tiangco announced that the city's government employees would receive {{Philippine peso|6,000}} ($117.41) each as compensation, totaling {{Philippine peso|6.4 million}} ($125,233.22). Tiangco also announced that their quarterly bonus payment would be released in advance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navotas releases P6.4 million for cash aid to employees amid lockdown |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255698-navotas-city-releases-budget-fund-incentives-employees-coronavirus |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Para\u00f1aque ====\nOn March 16, [[Para\u00f1aque]] Mayor Edwin Olivarez declared the city under a state of calamity due to the rise of COVID-19 cases in nearby areas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=COVID-19: Para\u00f1aque City placed under state of calamity |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243108/covid-19-paranaque-city-placed-under-state-of-calamity |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Mayor Olivarez declared a \"total lockdown\" on the city, prohibiting visitors \"without official business\" from entering the city's premises during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. The \"total lockdown\" permits only front line offices and basic services providers to operate throughout its duration. Olivarez also requested city hall employees to go on leave.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City implements \u2018total lockdown\u2019 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/paranaque-city-implements-total-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Mayor Olivarez announced that the city's front line workers, which he identified specifically as medical personnel, drug store personnel, health workers, supermarket employees, bank personnel, [[business process outsourcing]] personnel, restaurant personnel, and city government employees, would be provided with free transportation to their different workplaces.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City provides free transportation for city\u2019s frontliners, essential workers |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/19/paranaque-city-provides-free-transportation-for-citys-frontliners-essential-workers/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> That same day, Mayor Olivarez announced that both regular and contractualized employees in Para\u00f1aque would receive their full mid-year bonuses, in addition to a {{Philippine peso|6,000}} ($117) clothing allowance until March 23.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Abad |first1=Roderick |title=Para\u00f1aque City Hall workers get midyear bonus amid lockdown |url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/03/19/paranaque-city-hall-workers-get-midyear-bonus-amid-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=BusinessMirror |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the Para\u00f1aque government distributed around 100,000 relief goods to 14,000 \"vulnerable households\" across the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque City gov\u2019t to distribute relief goods house-to-house to vulnerable sectors |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/20/paranaque-city-govt-to-distribute-relief-goods-house-to-house-to-vulnerable-sectors/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Mayor Olivarez announced that the Para\u00f1aque government had begun imposing a 24-hour curfew to its residents.<ref>{{cite news |title=Para\u00f1aque imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/paraaque-imposes-24-hour-curfew |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> The following day, a photo published by the [[San Isidro, Para\u00f1aque|San Isidro]] government circulated on social media showing alleged curfew violators in the ''barangay'' being forced to sit under the sun as penalty. Netizens have criticized the action for physical torture.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Talabong |first1=Rambo |title=LOOK: In Para\u00f1aque, curfew violators sit under the sun as punishment |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255645-barangay-san-isidro-paranaque-curfew-violators-punished-sit-under-sun-curfew |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Pasay ====\nOn March 16, [[Pasay]] Mayor Emi Calixto-Rubiano declared the city under a state of calamity due to \"the extremely high incidence of COVID-19 cases in the city.\" The Pasay government also issued an ordinance imposing the 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nazario |first1=Dhel |title=Pasay City placed under a state of calamity |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/16/pasay-city-placed-under-a-state-of-calamity/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, Mayor Calixto-Rubiano ordered the advanced release of the thirteenth salary pay of city hall employees, in accordance with President Duterte's call for local government units to do so.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nazario |first1=Dhel |title=Pasay City mayor orders early release of 13th month pay, salaries of city hall employees |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/pasay-city-mayor-orders-early-release-of-13th-month-pay-salaries-of-city-hall-employees/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the Pasay government announced that it collaborated with the [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] to deploy [[food cart]]s to roam around the city's 201 ''barangays'' and sell essential goods such as food and medicines, in order to limit the movement of its residents during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. The Pasay government also announced that it collaborated with the [[Philippine Army]] to provide free transportation for Pasay-based health professionals and other service front liners who work outside the city, as well as persons with disabilities and senior citizens, amid the moratorium on public transportation; the government procured 100 electric tricycles and 20 [[Mitsubishi Delica|Mitsubishi L300]] vans.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=DTI to launch \u2018rolling stores\u2019 in Pasay amid quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245125/pasay-rolling-stores-during-quarantine |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the Pasay government ordered the installation of modular tents at the Pasay City Sports Complex and the Padre Burgos Elementary School to serve as [[Isolation (health care)|isolation units]] for COVID-19 PUIs in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Pasay sports complex, school transformed into isolation rooms for PUIs |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247741/pasay-govt-on-isolation-units-for-puis |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Pasig ====\nFollowing the confirmation of COVID-19 patient at [[The Medical City]] in the city's district of [[Ortigas Center|Ortigas]] on March 9, [[Pasig]] Mayor [[Vico Sotto]] ordered city officials to implement the guidelines of the DOH and the [[World Health Organization]] in preventing the spread of the virus, including contact tracing, organizing response teams, disinfecting public spaces, and the cancellation of all public events and gatherings.<ref name=\"Sotto\">{{cite news |last1=Abellon |first1=Bam |title=Here\u2019s everything that Mayor Vico Sotto has done so far in response to COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/03/20/20/heres-everything-that-mayor-vico-sotto-has-done-so-far-in-response-to-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Around 500 sets of [[personal protective equipment]] were distributed by city government on March 14 to its 30 ''barangays''. The city council also approved an ordinance imposing the 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guzman |first1=Jimmyley |title=Sprayers, protective equipment distributed to Pasig barangays |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036318 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |publisher=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Sotto approved the declaration of a state of claamity in Pasig on March 15 after six confirmed cases and one fatality were recorded in the city. The mayor also announced that they have ordered a mandatory isolation for the health workers of Rizal Medical Center after they were exposed to a confirmed coronavirus patient.<ref name=\"state of calamity\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/16/2001178/more-cities-metro-manila-under-state-calamity |title=More cities in Metro Manila under state of calamity |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Servallos, N.J. |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Pasig City Council on March 16 approved an anti-panic buying and hoarding of essential goods ordinance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bigtas |first1=Jannielyn Ann |title=Pasig City to implement anti-panic buying, hoarding ordinance |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729913/pasig-city-to-implement-anti-panic-buying-hoarding-ordinance/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Sotto appealed to the [[Department of Interior and Local Government]] (DILG) on March 17 to allow the operation of [[Motorized tricycle (Philippines)|tricycles]] and the city's bus service to specifically transport front line health professionals and other essential service providers to the city's hospitals during the quarantine period, following the moratorium on mass public transportation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vico Sotto rejects ban on tricycles in Pasig City amid Luzon lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/vico-sotto-rejects-ban-on-tricycles-in-pasig-city-amid-luzon-lockdown |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Pasig City sets up sanitation tents outside hospitals, provides bus service for healthcare workers |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/lifestyle/healthandwellness/730259/pasig-city-sets-up-sanitation-tents-outside-city-hall-pcgh-children-s-hospital/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Sotto had earlier raised tricycles fares by 50 percent following the decline in residents leaving their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Vico Sotto temporarily allows tricycles in Pasig for people reporting to work amid quarantine |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/17/164402/vico-sotto-temporarily-allows-tricycles-in-pasig-for-people-reporting-to-work-amid-quarantine/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Tricycle drivers were mandated by the city government to transport a maximum of three passengers per ride in observance of the national government's social distancing guidelines.<ref name=\"Sotto\"/>\n\nOn March 18, Mayor Sotto pledged to give both [[Endo contractualization#Regular employment|regular]] and contractualized government employees their full salaries during the duration of the \"enhanced\" community quarantine in Luzon, while emergency front line workers would receive hazard and overtime pays.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Pasig City Hall employees, from regular to contractual ones, to get full salaries amid enhanced quarantine |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730108/pasig-employees-to-get-full-salaries-hazard-pay-amid-enhanced-quarantine/story/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The Pasig government also assembled sanitation tents at the entrances of the city hall and two hospitals, prepared food packages containing vitamins to be distributed to the city's \"vulnerable households\",<ref name=\"Sotto\"/> and purchased three [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|octocopter drones]] to be utilized for disinfecting public spaces.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=Vico Sotto has been stellar with his proactive COVID-19 initiatives, and Filipinos want him to lead the whole country |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/18/164558/vico-sotto-has-been-stellar-with-his-proactive-covid-19-initiatives-and-filipinos-want-him-to-lead-the-whole-country/ |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Sotto ordered the Dahlia Hotel in the city on March 19 to be converted into a quarantine facility able to accommodate at least 300 PUMs and PUIs with mild to moderate symptoms of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Sotto\"/> That same day, the DILG rejected Mayor Sotto's appeal on operating tricycles in Pasig claiming it violates the national government's directives to observe social distancing measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reysio-Cruz |first1=Matthew |title=Vico Sotto defends tricycle proposal amid DILG objection |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245279/sotto-defends-tricycle-proposal-amid-dilg-objection |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The Pasig government responded by commissioning two electric-powered City Optimized Managed Electric Transport jeeps to transport the city's front line workers across Pasig to its hospitals.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reyes |first1=Kate |title=Check out Pasig's earth-friendly rides for hospital frontliners |url=https://www.spin.ph/life/cars-and-tech/pasig-city-to-provide-earth-friendly-rides-to-hospital-frontliners-a2442-20200319 |website=Spin.ph |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe deadlines of all tax payments, rent, permits, and other obligatory submissions were extended on March 24 by the city government for two months.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kabagani |first1=Lade Jean |title=Deadline of tax payments, other gov\u2019t fees extended in Pasig City |url=http://www.canadianinquirer.net/2020/03/25/deadline-of-tax-payments-other-govt-fees-extended-in-pasig-city/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |via=''Philippine Canadian Inquirer'' |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFive trucks were deployed by the Pasig government on March 25 transporting loads of essential goods, such as food, to different ''barangays'' in the city, where they are sold to residents. The government labeled these trucks as \"mobile ''[[palengke]]s''\", aimed at limiting the movement of people during the community quarantine. The essential goods sold to residents through the trucks are sourced from the vendors of the city's public markets \"to assist them generate income.\" About 400,000 food packs were also distributed by the city government to Pasig residents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kabagani |first1=Lade Jean |title=Pasig City's 'mobile palengke' boosts social distancing |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097797 |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Pasig government also began giving the city's jeepney, tricycle, and [[UV Express]] drivers financial assistance of {{Philippine peso|3,000}} ($59) each for a total of {{Philippine peso|55.5 million}} ($1.1 million) starting March 30.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurel |first1=Drei |title=Thousands of Pasig City PUV drivers to get P3,000 financial aid starting next week |url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/news/motoring-news/pasig-city-puv-financial-assistance-a962-20200326 |website=Top Gear Philippines |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Quezon City ====\n\nOn March 13, [[Quezon City]] Mayor [[Joy Belmonte]] announced a state of calamity for the city following six confirmed cases of local COVID-19 transmissions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Quezon City declares state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/qc-state-of-calamity.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Mayor Belmonte issued an executive order on March 15 imposing the 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tuquero |first1=Loreben |title=Belmonte imposes 8 pm to 5 am curfew in Quezon City |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254626-joy-belmonte-imposes-curfew-quezon-city |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The [[Quezon City University]] has been used as a quarantine site for PUIs in the city. As of March 24 at least 379,000 food packs has been distributed to residents by the Quezon City government.<ref name=\"covidqcnow72\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19 cases in QC now at 72; four die, one recovers |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731197/covid-19-cases-in-qc-now-at-72-four-die-one-recovers/story/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, the Quezon City government partnered with [[Hotel Sogo]] and the Rainbow Place Dormitory in [[Quezon City#Tandang Sora|Tandang Sora]] to provide free accommodations for service front liners, especially health professionals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tuquero |first1=Loreben |title=Quezon City provides free lodging for health workers |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255986-quezon-city-free-lodging-health-workers-coronavirus |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, the Quezon City government imposed an executive order prohibiting the sale, purchase, and consumption of alcoholic beverages in public places during the \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=QC imposes liquor ban until end of Luzon-wide quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249257/qc-imposes-liquor-ban-until-end-of-luzon-wide-quarantine |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== San Juan ====\nOn March 6, the [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] government ordered the temporary closure of a Muslim prayer hall at the [[Greenhills Shopping Center]] after a frequent visitor of the pay hall was reported as the country's fifth case of confirmed COVID-19 diagnosis. San Juan Mayor [[Francis Zamora]] also ordered the postponement of all scheduled public events in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=San Juan prayer hall frequented by coronavirus patient temporarily closed |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/san-juan-muslim-prayer-hall-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Mayor Zamora announced that the villages of Greenhills and West Crame were identified as coronavirus hotspots after four salon workers in Greenhills tested positive for the virus. Zamora thus declared a state of calamity in the city and ordered the temporary closure of all malls in the city, as well as all churches.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Zamora: Malls in San Juan City temporarily closed starting March 15; curfew ordinance to follow |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/14/zamora-malls-in-san-juan-city-temporarily-closed-starting-march-15-curfew-ordinance-to-follow/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The city council had also passed an ordinance imposing the 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew agreed upon by the Metro Manila Council.<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n\nOn March 26, Mayor Zamora announced that the San Juan government had reached an agreement with [[Xavier School]] to convert the San Juan City Science High School into a 100-bed isolation facility for COVID-19 PUIs in the city. Xavier School would assist the government in providing necessary medical equipment, medicines, and front line personnel.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=San Juan City to use public high school building as quarantine facility |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248832/san-juan-city-to-use-high-school-building-as-quarantine-facility |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Taguig ====\nOn March 17, [[Taguig]] Mayor [[Lino Cayetano]] ordered a lockdown on the city after four of its residents tested positive for COVID-19; the lockdown only permits delivery vehicles of basic goods and supplies to enter and exit Taguig.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taguig placed on lockdown to prevent coronavirus spread |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/lockdown-taguig-coronavirus-cvoid-19-community-quarantine |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Cayetano also said that the city government collaborated with transportation groups and ''barangays'' to organize [[Premium Point-to-Point Bus Service|point-to-point transportation services]] for its residents to access basic supplies amid the moratorium on mass public transportation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Taguig City on lockdown starting Wednesday amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/Taguig-City-lockdown-Wednesday-COVID-19.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Cayetano warned the ''barangay'' officials of Taguig against collecting payment fees while issuing the city's health professionals and other essential workers special permits to freely roam around the city at any time during the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Jel |title=Mayor Cayetano stops money collection of barangays for travel permit |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/mayor-cayetano-stops-money-collection-of-barangays-for-travel-permit/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the \"enhanced\" community quarantine, health workers from the Taguig health office had been distributing [[condom]]s, [[birth control pill]]s, [[Tuberculosis management|medication for tuberculosis]] and [[HIV medication|HIV]], and vitamins for [[hypertension]] and [[diabetes]] to residents for free.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Sex in the time of COVID-19: Taguig City gives pills, condoms to residents |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248796/sex-in-the-time-of-covid-19-taguig-city-gives-pills-condoms-to-residents |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Valenzuela ====\n\nOn March 13, the [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]] city council approved an ordinance prohibiting the hoarding and panic buying of essential goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Anti-hoarding, anti-panic buying ordinance to be implemented in Valenzuela |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729483/anti-hoarding-anti-panic-buying-ordinance-to-be-implemented-in-valenzuela/story/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Valenzuela Mayor [[Rex Gatchalian]] announced the cancellation of several scheduled events, namely the Top Taxpayers and Top Job Providers\u2019 Night and Concert, Mega Job Fair, and the weekend Family Day activities in public schools, to prevent the spread of the virus amongst large crowds.<ref name=\"Caloocan, Valenzuela\"/>\n\nOn March 16, Mayor Gatchalian placed Valenzuela under a state of calamity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Valenzuela City placed under state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/valenzuela-city-placed-under-state-of-calamity-amid-covid-19-threat |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, Mayor Gatchalian announced that {{Philippine peso|500\u2212700|link=yes}}-worth of vouchers would be issued to some 75,000 Valenzuela\u00f1o families for which they could use to claim essential goods at groceries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Valenzuela City to issue food vouchers during Luzon lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/video/news/03/19/20/valenzuela-city-to-issue-food-vouchers-during-luzon-lockdown |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The city's government would also distribute food packages to families registered under the [[conditional cash transfer]] program.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baron |first1=Gabriela |title=Valenzuela to distribute food packs to citizens at risk of poverty |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/valenzuela-to-distribute-food-packs-to-citizens-at-risk-of-poverty/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Gatchalian assured the city's health professionals that they would be issued special permits for easier entry into the city borders, amid the establishment of checkpoints in accordance with the national government's directives regarding the partial lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Mayor Gatchalian assures health workers of easy entry into Valenzuela despite Luzon quarantine |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/mayor-gatchalian-assures-health-workers-of-easy-entry-into-valenzuela-despite-luzon-quarantine/ |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the Valenzuela government established two centralized isolation centers to accommodate suspected cases of COVID-19 and confirmed patients.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Valenzuela sets up isolation centers vs. COVID-19 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730438/valenzuela-sets-up-isolation-centers-vs-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, the Valenzuela city council passed an ordinance prohibiting the sale, distribution, and consumption of alcoholic beverages during the \"enhanced\" community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hallare |first1=Katrina |title=Valenzuela imposes liquor ban during enhanced community quarantine period |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248511/valenzuela-imposes-liquor-ban-during-enhanced-community-quarantine-period |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n[[File:Podium Mall coronavirus sign warning.jpg|thumb|A coronavirus warning sign at the entrance of [[The Podium]] mall in [[Ortigas Center]], [[Mandaluyong]], February 29, 2020]]\n\nOn March 11, the [[Wack Wack Golf and Country Club]] in Mandaluyong temporarily closed after one of its guests, a Singaporean permanent resident, was confirmed to have contracted COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong golf club shut after guest tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/11/coronavirus-sanitation-wack-wack-golf-club.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/exclusive-philippine-golf-club-on-lockdown-after-guest-from-singapore-tests-positive | title=Philippine golf club on lockdown after Singapore guest tests positive for coronavirus| date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Manila]] and the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cubao|Diocese of Cubao]] announced that it would suspend the celebration of [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Masses]] and other public gatherings in all its churches \"until further notice\", in an effort to curb the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Catholic churches in Metro Manila suspend masses |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/No-masses-Manila-archdiocese-churches-COVID-19.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the MMDA's imposition of an area-wide curfew during the Metro Manila lockdown, mall operators [[Ayala Malls]], [[SM Supermalls]], [[Robinsons Malls]], and [[Vista Malls]] initially announced that it would shorten the operating hours of its malls in Metro Manila, from 11{{nbsp}}a.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m., in response.<ref>{{cite news |title=Metro Manila malls to shut down early ahead of quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/14/20/metro-manila-quarantine-malls-to-shut-down-early-ahead-of-quarantine |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> However, Metro Manila city governments later passed ordinances mandating the temporary closure of malls with the exception of establishments providing essential goods and services (such as supermarkets, pharmacies, and banks) from March 16 \"until further notice\", in accordance with the joint resolution passed by the Metro Manila Council regarding the lockdown.<ref>{{cite web |title=UPDATED: Which NCR malls are closed and which cities have curfew? See list |url=https://www.spin.ph/life/active-lifestyle/possible-mall-closures-eyed-as-ncr-goes-into-curfew-starting-tomorrow-a1374-20200314 |website=Spin.ph |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident Duterte's March 16 declaration of a month-long \"enhanced\" community quarantine on the island of Luzon, including Metro Manila, suspended the operations of all modes of [[public transportation in Metro Manila]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=San Juan |first1=Alexandria Dennise |title=Operation of all modes of public transportation in Luzon suspended \u2013 DOTr |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/operation-of-all-modes-of-public-transportation-in-luzon-suspended-dotr/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[Metro Rail Transit Corporation]] and [[Light Rail Transit Authority]] suspended the operations of the [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System]] and the [[Manila Light Rail Transit System]], respectively, from March 17; [[Manila Light Rail Transit System Line 1|LRT Line 1]] would resume operations on April 12, while [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System Line 3|MRT Line 3]] would lift its suspension on April 13.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jazul |first1=Noreen |title=MRT, LRT announce temporary suspension of operations |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/mrt-lrt-announce-temporary-suspension-of-operations/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP) reported that [[Crime in the Philippines|crime rates in Metro Manila]] decreased by almost 70 percent, according to data between March 15 to 20 during the implementation of the partial Metro Manila lockdown and the Luzon-wide \"enhanced\" community quarantine. During that period, the PNP reported only seven cases of murder, ten cases of homicide, 11 cases of physical injury (compared to 41 last year), five cases of rape (compared to 23 last year), 18 cases of robbery (compared to 50 last year), and 24 cases of theft (compared to 68 last year). The PNP attributed the decline in crime rates to the implementation of strict home quarantine measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rucuenco |first1=Aaron |title=Crime rate down by 70% in Metro Manila, 77.3% in Central Luzon due to lockdown |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/22/crime-rate-down-by-70-in-metro-manila-77-3-in-central-luzon-due-to-lockdown/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy March 26, eight [[List of hospitals in Metro Manila|private hospitals in Metro Manila]] announced that it had reached its maximum capacity to handle any COVID-19-related case. These hospitals were namely the [[Asian Hospital and Medical Center]] in [[Alabang]], [[Muntinlupa]];<ref>{{cite news |last1=Damicog |first1=Jeffrey |title=Asian Hospital declares full capacity |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/26/asian-hospital-declares-full-capacity/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> [[Chinese General Hospital and Medical Center]] in [[Santa Cruz, Manila]]; [[De Los Santos Medical Center]] in [[Quezon City]]; [[Makati Medical Center]] in [[Makati]]; Marikina Valley Medical Center in [[Marikina]]; [[The Medical City]] in [[Ortigas Center]], [[Pasig]]; and both hospitals of [[St. Luke's Medical Center]] in [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Quezon City|Quezon City]] and [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Global City|Bonifacio Global City]], [[Taguig]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yamsuan |first1=Cathy Ca\u00f1ares |last2=Yee |first2=Jovic |title=5 Metro Manila hospitals reach full capacity for COVID-19 cases |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247913/5-metro-hospitals-reach-full-capacity-for-covid-19-cases |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Malasig |first1=Jeline |title=With a heavy heart, two more Metro Manila hospitals stop admission of COVID-19 patients as they reach 'full capacity' |url=https://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/03/25/165031/with-a-heavy-heart-two-more-metro-manila-hospitals-stop-admission-of-covid-19-patients-as-they-reached-full-capacity/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=InterAksyon |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=More major Metro Manila hospitals declare full capacity, shut to COVID-19 patients |url=https://coconuts.co/manila/news/more-major-metro-manila-hospitals-declare-full-capacity-shut-to-covid-19-patients/ |website=Coconuts Manila |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources]] (DENR) reported that the [[air quality index]] of different cities in Metro Manila had improved, following the implementation of the \"enhanced\" community quarantine on Luzon. The cities with the lowest amounts of inhalable [[PM10|coarse particulate matter]] (PM<sub>10</sub>) were Para\u00f1aque (7), Marikina (9), San Juan (17), Malabon (22), Taguig (32), and Pasay (43), all reporting \"good\" values of air quality; meanwhile, the cities of Pasig (53), Makati (54), Las Pi\u00f1as (86), and Northern Caloocan (92) all reported \"moderate/fair\" values. The DENR collected the data after photos surfaced on social media depicting [[smog]]-free skylines of some of the aforementioned cities, which is likely a result of minimized activity due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laurel |first1=Drei |title=DENR data shows improved air quality in Metro Manila due to quarantine |url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/news/motoring-news/denr-air-quality-metro-manila-a962-20200325 |website=Top Gear Philippines |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Philippines}}\n*[[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine]]\n*[[List of disasters in Metro Manila by death toll]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Metro Manila}}\n* [https://www.doh.gov.ph/2019-nCoV Updates on Novel Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19)] by the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]], Situation tracker, updated daily.\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:History of Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Health in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by city|Manila]]\n", "name_user": "Night Lantern", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Metro_Manila"}
{"title_page": "Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=July 2014}}\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2)\n| logo                   = [[File:AWS Simple Icons Compute Amazon EC2 Instances.svg|200px]]\n| logo caption           = Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2)\n| screenshot             = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| caption                = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = Amazon.com, Inc.\n| developer              = [[Amazon.com]]\n| released               = {{Start date and age|2006|08|25}} (public beta)\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest preview version = \n| status                 = Active\n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Linux]]\n* [[Microsoft Windows]]\n* [[FreeBSD]]\n}}\n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = English\n| genre                  = [[Virtual private server]]\n| license                = [[Proprietary software]]\n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/}}\n}}\n\n'''Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud''' ('''EC2''') forms a central part of [[Amazon.com]]'s [[cloud-computing]] platform, [[Amazon Web Services]] (AWS), by allowing users to rent [[virtual computer]]s on which to run their own computer applications. EC2 encourages scalable deployment of applications by providing a [[web service]] through which a user can boot an [[Amazon Machine Image]] (AMI) to configure a [[Virtual Machine|virtual machine]], which Amazon calls an \"instance\", containing any software desired. A user can create, launch, and terminate [[Server (computing)|server]]-instances as needed, paying by the second for active servers{{snd}}hence the term \"elastic\". EC2 provides users with control over the geographical location of instances that allows for [[latency (disambiguation)|latency]] optimization and high levels of [[Redundancy (engineering)|redundancy]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.news.com/8301-10784_3-9904091-7.html\n |title=Amazon Web Services adds 'resiliency' to EC2 compute service\n |first=Martin\n |last=LaMonica\n |work=[[CNET]]\n |date=March 27, 2008\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, Amazon switched its own retail website to use EC2 and AWS.<ref>\n{{Cite AV media|title=AWS Cloud Tour 2011 {{!}} Australia: Event Highlights|URL=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uf07L1RUOW4|medium=video}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Timeline of Amazon Web Services}}\nAmazon announced a limited public beta test of EC2 on August 25, 2006,<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2006/08/amazon_ec2_beta.html\n |title=Amazon EC2 Beta\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=August 25, 2006\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate= May 31, 2013\n}}</ref> offering access on a first-come, first-served basis.\nAmazon added two new instance types (Large and Extra-Large) on October 16, 2007.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2007/10/amazon-ec2-gets.html\n |title=Amazon EC2 Gets More Muscle\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=October 16, 2007\n}}</ref> On May 29, 2008, two more types were added, High-CPU Medium and High-CPU Extra Large.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/05/more-ec2-power.html\n |title=More EC2 power\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=May 29, 2008\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}</ref> There were twelve types of instances available.<ref>[http://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/ Amazon EC2 Instances]. Aws.amazon.com. Retrieved on 2013-08-09.</ref>\n\nAmazon added three new features on March 27, 2008,<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/03/new-ec2-feature.html\n |title=New EC2 Features\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=March 27, 2008\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}</ref> static IP addresses, availability zones, and user selectable kernels.\nOn August 20, 2008, Amazon added [[Elastic Block Store]] (EBS)<ref name=\"ebs\">{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/08/amazon-elastic.html\n |title=Amazon EBS (Elastic Block Store) - Bring Us Your Data\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date= August 20, 2008\n |accessdate= May 31, 2013\n |work= Amazon Web Services Blog\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110328011236/http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/08/amazon-elastic.html| archivedate= March 28, 2011 |url-status= live}}</ref>\nThis provides persistent storage, a feature that had been lacking since the service was introduced.\n\nAmazon EC2 went into full production when it dropped the beta label on October 23, 2008. On the same day, Amazon announced the following features:<ref name=\"BigDayForEC2\">{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/10/big-day-for-ec2.html\n |title=Big Day For EC2\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=August 23, 2008\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}</ref>\na service level agreement for EC2,\n[[Microsoft Windows]] in beta form on EC2,\n[[Microsoft SQL Server]] in beta form on EC2,\nplans for an AWS management console, and\nplans for load balancing, autoscaling, and cloud monitoring services.<ref name=\"BigDayForEC2\"/> These features were subsequently added on May 18, 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2009/05/new-aws-load-balancing-automatic-scaling-and-cloud-monitoring-services.html\n |title=New Features for EC2\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=May 18, 2009\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nAmazon EC2 was developed mostly by a team in [[Cape Town, South Africa]] led by Chris Pinkham.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://itknowledgeexchange.techtarget.com/cloud-computing/2010/06/17/amazons-early-efforts-at-cloud-computing-partly-accidental/\n|title=Amazon's early efforts at cloud computing? Partly accidental\n|date=June 17, 2010}}</ref>\nPinkham provided the initial architecture guidance for EC2 and then built the team and led the development of the project along with [[Willem van Biljon]].\n\n==Instance types==\nInitially, EC2 used [[Xen]] virtualization exclusively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citrix.com/global-partners/amazon-web-services.html |title=Citrix and Amazon Web Services (AWS) |date= |publisher=citrix.com |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> However, on November 6, 2017, Amazon announced<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/now-available-compute-intensive-c5-instances-for-amazon-ec2/ |title=Now Available \u2013 Compute-Intensive C5 Instances for Amazon EC2|date= |accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref> the new C5 family of instances that were based on a custom architecture around the [[Kernel-based Virtual Machine|KVM hypervisor]], called Nitro.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/faqs/#compute-optimized |title=Amazon EC2 FAQs |date= |accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o9_4uGvbvnk |title=AWS re:Invent 2017: NEW LAUNCH! Amazon EC2 Bare Metal Instances (CMP330)|date=|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Each virtual machine, called an \"instance\", functions as a [[virtual private server]]. Amazon sizes instances based on \"Elastic Compute Units\". The performance of otherwise identical virtual machines may vary.<ref>J. Dejun, G. Pierre and C.-H. Chi. [http://www.globule.org/publi/EPARPSOA_nfpsla2009.html EC2 Performance Analysis for Resource Provisioning of Service-Oriented Applications]. In Proceedings of the Workshop on Non-Functional Properties and SLA Management in Service-Oriented Computing, November 2009.</ref> On November 28, 2017, AWS announced a bare-metal instance type offering marking a remarkable departure from exclusively offering virtualized instance types.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/28/aws-launches-bare-metal-instances/ |title=AWS launches bare metal instances |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |date=November 28, 2017 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2019, the following instance types were offered:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/|title=Amazon EC2 Instance Types \u2013 Amazon Web Services (AWS)|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref>\n* General Purpose: A1, T3, T2, M5, M5a, M4, T3a\n* Compute Optimized: C5, C5n, C4\n* Memory Optimized: R5, R5a, R4, X1e, X1, High Memory, z1d\n* Accelerated Computing: P3, P2, G3, F1\n* Storage Optimized: H1, I3, D2\n{{As of |April 2018}}, the following paying method for instance were offered:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aws.amazon.com/ec2/pricing/ |title=Amazon EC2 Pricing |date= |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n* On-demand: pay by the hour without commitment.\n* Reserved: rent instances with one-time payment receiving discounts on the hourly charge.\n* Spot: bid-based service: runs the jobs only if the spot price is below the bid specified by bidder. The spot price is claimed to be supply-demand based, however a 2011 study concluded that the price was generally not set to clear the market, but was dominated by an undisclosed [[reserve price]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/users/wwwb/cgi-bin/tr-info.cgi/2011/CS/CS-2011-09 |title=Technical Report CS-2011-09 |publisher=cs.technion.ac.il |date= |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Cost===\n[[File:AmazonWebServicesPriceReductions.JPG|thumb|Amazon CTO Werner Vogels announces price reductions at AWS Summit 2013 NYC]]\n{{As of |2018|04}}, Amazon charged about $0.0058/hour ($4.176/month) for the smallest \"Nano Instance\" (t2.nano) virtual machine running Linux or Windows. Storage-optimized instances cost as much as $4.992/hour (i3.16xlarge). \"Reserved\" instances can go as low as $2.50/month for a three-year prepaid plan.<ref group=\"note\">$109 for a three-year Heavy Utilization Reserved t2.micro Instances reservation amortized over thirty-six months plus one month at $0.002/hour.</ref><ref>[http://aws.amazon.com/ec2/#pricing Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2), Cloud Computing Servers]. Aws.amazon.com (2014-07-01). Retrieved on 2014-07-01.</ref> The data transfer charge ranges from free to $0.12 per gigabyte, depending on the direction and monthly volume (inbound data transfer is free on all AWS services<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2011/06/aws-lowers-its-pricing-again-free-inbound-data-transfer-and-lower-outbound-data-transfer-for-all-ser.html\n |title=AWS Lowers its Pricing Again!&nbsp;\u2013 No Inbound Data Transfer Fees and Lower Outbound Data Transfer for All Services including Amazon CloudFront\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |work=[[Typepad]]\n |date=June 29, 2011\n|accessdate=July 6, 2011\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110707085314/http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2011/06/aws-lowers-its-pricing-again-free-inbound-data-transfer-and-lower-outbound-data-transfer-for-all-ser.html| archivedate= July 7, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>).\n\n===Free tier===\n{{As of|2010|December}} Amazon offered a bundle of free resource credits to new account holders. The credits are designed to run a \"micro\" sized server, storage (EBS), and bandwidth for one year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/free/|title=AWS Free Tier|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.}}</ref> Unused credits cannot be carried over from one month to the next.<ref>{{Cite web|title = FAQs|url = http://aws.amazon.com/free/faqs/|website = Amazon Web Services, Inc.|accessdate = 2015-07-31}}</ref>\n\n===Reserved Instances===\nReserved instances enable EC2 or RDS service users to reserve an instance for one or three years. The corresponding hourly rate charged by Amazon to operate the instance is 35-75% lower than the rate charged for on-demand instances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2011/12/reserved-instance-options-for-amazon-ec2.html|title=Additional Reserved Instance Options for Amazon EC2|publisher=Amazon}}</ref>\nReserved Instances can be purchased in three different ways: All Upfront, Partial Upfront and No Upfront. The different purchase options allow for different structuring of payment models.\nIn September 2016, AWS announced several enhancements to Reserved Instances, introducing a new feature called scope and a new reservation type called a Convertible.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cloudhealthtech.com/blog/quick-start-guide-aws-regional-convertible-reservations |title=A Quick Start Guide To AWS Regional & Convertible Reservations |publisher=[[CloudHealth Technologies]] |first= Alan |last=Santos |date=September 29, 2016 |access-date=2016-10-04}}</ref> In October 2017, AWS announced the allowance to subdivide the instances purchased for more flexibility <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/3180821/cloud-computing/aws-follows-google-with-reserved-instance-flexibility-changes.html |title=AWS Follows Google With Reserved Instance Flexibility Changes |first=Blair |last=Hanley Frank |work=[[PC World]] |date=March 14, 2017 |access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref>\n\n===Spot Instances===\nCloud providers maintain large amounts of excess capacity they have to sell or risk incurring losses.<ref name=\"ladypine\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/~ladypine/spotprice-ieee.pdf|title=Deconstructing Amazon EC2 Spot Instance Pricing|last=Technion - Israel Institute of Technology|date=|publisher=Technion University |access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref>\nAmazon EC2 Spot instances are spare compute capacity in the AWS cloud available at up to 90% discount compared to On-Demand prices. As a trade-off, AWS offers no [[Service-level agreement|SLA]] on these instances and customers take the risk that it can be interrupted with only two minutes of notification when Amazon needs the capacity back. Researchers from the Israeli Institute of Technology found that \"they (Spot instances) are typically generated at random from within a tight price interval via a dynamic hidden reserve price\".<ref name=\"ladypine\" /> Some companies, like Spotinst, are using big data combined with machine learning to predict spot interruptions up to 15 minutes in advance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thenewstack.io/spotinst-making-cheaper-excess-compute-capacity/ |title=Spotinst: Making the Most of Cheaper Excess Compute Capacity |first=Susan |last=Hall |date=December 26, 2017 |work=The News Stack |access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/25/spotnist-delivers-spot-cloud-infrastructure-services-at-discount-prices/|title=Spotinst delivers spot cloud infrastructure services at discount prices|last=Miller |first=Ron |date=October 25, 2017 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Savings Plans ===\nIn November 2019, Amazon announced Savings Plans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/savingsplans/|title=New \u2013 Savings Plans for AWS Compute Services|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Savings Plans are an alternative to Reserved Instances<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gorillastack.com/news/aws-savings-plans-reserved-instances/|title=Savings Plans vs Reserved Instances|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> that come in 2 different plan types: Compute Savings Plans and EC2 Instances Savings Plans. Compute Savings Plans allow an organisation to commit to EC2 and Fargate usage with the freedom to change region, family, size, availability zone, OS and tenancy inside the lifespan of the commitment. EC2 Instance Savings plans provide the lowest prices but are less flexible meaning a user must commit to individual instance families within a region to take advantage, but with the freedom to change instances within the family in that region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/savingsplans/faq/|title=AWS Savings Plans FAQ|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\n\n===Operating systems===\n{{Further|operating system}}\nWhen it launched in August 2006, the EC2 service offered [[Linux]] and later [[Sun Microsystems]]' [[OpenSolaris]] and [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris Express Community Edition]]. In October 2008, EC2 added the [[Windows Server 2003]] and [[Windows Server 2008]] operating systems to the list of available [[operating system]]s.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17939_109-10073696-2.html\n |title=Amazon's Linux cloud computing out of beta, joined by Windows\n |first=Stephen\n |last=Shankland\n |work=[[CNET]]\n |date=October 23, 2008\n|accessdate=October 24, 2008\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.amazon.com/windows/\n |title=Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) Running Microsoft Windows Server and SQL Server\n |date=October 23, 2008\n|accessdate=October 25, 2008\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081201023846/http://aws.amazon.com/windows/| archivedate= 1 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nIn March 2011, [[NetBSD]] AMIs became available.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.netbsd.org/tnf/entry/netbsd_now_runs_under_amazon |title=NetBSD now runs under Amazon EC2 |first=Jean-Yves |last=Migeon |work=NetBSD Blog |date=March 13, 2011 |accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> In November 2012, [[Windows Server 2012]] support was added.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2012/11/windows-server-2012-now-available-on-aws.html\n |title=Windows Server 2012 Now Available on AWS\n |date=November 19, 2012\n|accessdate=March 26, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nSince 2006, Colin Percival, a FreeBSD developer and Security Officer, solicited Amazon to add FreeBSD.<ref name=\"YT interview\">{{cite web|last1=Barr|first1=Jeff|title=Interview - Live from AWS re:Invent Colin Percival, FreeBSD Developer|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SK7EeV_GD3M|publisher=Amazon Web Services 28.11.2012|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> In November 2012, Amazon officially supported running [[FreeBSD]] in EC2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2012/11/aws-marketplace-additional-operating-system-support.html|title=AWS Marketplace \u2013 Additional EC2 Operating System Support (FreeBSD, Debian, CentOS)|publisher=Amazon}}</ref><ref name=CP-FreeBSDonEC2HowTo>{{cite web|last1=Percival|first1=Colin|title=How to build FreeBSD/EC2 images|url=http://www.daemonology.net/blog/2014-02-16-FreeBSD-EC2-build.html|publisher=Colin Percival|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=CP-FreeBSD-EC2>{{cite web|last1=Percival|first1=Colin|title=FreeBSD on EC2|url=http://www.daemonology.net/freebsd-on-ec2/|publisher=Colin Percival|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> The FreeBSD/EC2 platform is maintained by Percival<ref name=AWS-ColinPercival>{{cite web|title=Colin Percival|url=https://aws.amazon.com/marketplace/seller-profile?id=4a931b8a-95f6-4bb2-8b7e-53507851c459|website=awsmarketplace|publisher=Amazon Web Services, Inc.|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> who also developed the secure [[Data deduplication|deduplicating]] [[Amazon S3]]-cloud based backup service [[Tarsnap]].<ref name=TarsnapCP>{{cite web|last1=Percival|first1=Colin|title=About Tarsnap|url=http://www.tarsnap.com/about.html|publisher=Tarsnap and C. Percival|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmazon has their own Linux distribution based on the [[Fedora (operating system)|Fedora]] and [[Red Hat Enterprise Linux]] as a low cost offering known as the [[Amazon Machine Image|Amazon Linux AMI]]. Version 2013.03 included:<ref>{{cite web |title= Amazon Linux AMI 2013.03 Release Notes |work= AWS web site |url= http://aws.amazon.com/amazon-linux-ami/2013.03-release-notes/ |accessdate= May 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n* [[Linux kernel]] version 3.4.34\n* Java [[OpenJDK]] Runtime Environment (IcedTea6 1.11.4)\n* [[GNU Compiler Collection]] gcc.x86_64 4.4.6-3.45.amzn1\n\n===Persistent storage===\nAn EC2 instance may be launched with a choice of two types of storage for its boot disk or \"root device.\" The first option is a local \"instance-store\" disk as a root device (originally the only choice). The second option is to use an EBS volume as a root device. Instance-store volumes are temporary storage, which survive rebooting an EC2 instance, but when the instance is stopped or terminated (e.g., by an API call, or due to a failure), this store is lost.\n\nThe [[Amazon Elastic Block Store]] (EBS) provides raw [[block devices]] that can be attached to Amazon EC2 instances. These block devices can then be used like any raw block device. In a typical use case, this would include formatting the device with a [[filesystem]] and [[mounting (computing)|mounting]] it. In addition, EBS supports a number of advanced storage features, including snapshotting and cloning. EBS volumes can be up to 16TB in size. EBS volumes are built on replicated storage, so that the failure of a single component will not cause data loss.\nEBS was introduced to the general public by Amazon in August 2008.<ref name=\"ebs\" />\n\n[[File:AWS Simple Icons Storage Amazon EBS.svg|right|70px|Amazon EBS]]\nEBS volumes provide persistent storage independent of the lifetime of the EC2 instance, and act much like hard drives on a real server. More accurately, they appear as block devices to the operating system that are backed by Amazon's disk arrays. The OS is free to use the device however it wants. In the most common case, a file system is loaded and the volume acts as a hard drive. Another possible use is the creation of RAID arrays by combining two or more EBS volumes. RAID allows increases of speed and/or reliability of EBS. Users can set up and manage storage volumes of sizes from 1GB to 16TB. The volumes support snapshots, which can be taken from a GUI tool or the API. EBS volumes can be attached or detached from instances while they are running, and moved from one instance to another.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://1201restart.com/Articles/Introduction_to_EBS_Volumes\n |title        = Introduction to EBS Volumes\n |publisher    = 1201 Restart.com\n |date         = December 2010\n |accessdate   = December 18, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110513114653/http://1201restart.com/Articles/Introduction_to_EBS_Volumes\n |archive-date = 2011-05-13\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n[[Amazon S3|Simple Storage Service (S3)]] is a storage system in which data is accessible to EC2 instances, or directly over the network to suitably authenticated callers (all communication is over HTTP). Amazon does not charge for the bandwidth for communications between EC2 instances and S3 storage \"in the same region.\" Accessing S3 data stored in a different region (for example, data stored in Europe from a US East Coast EC2 instance) will be billed at Amazon's normal rates.\n\nS3-based storage is priced per gigabyte per month. Applications access S3 through an API. For example, [[Hadoop|Apache Hadoop]] supports a special s3: filesystem to support reading from and writing to S3 storage during a [[MapReduce]] job. There are also S3 filesystems for Linux, which mount a remote S3 filestore on an EC2 image, as if it were local storage. As S3 is not a full [[POSIX]] filesystem, things may not behave the same as on a local disk (e.g., no locking support).\n\n===Elastic IP addresses===\n[[File:AWS Simple Icons Compute Amazon EC2 Elastic IP.svg|70px|right|Amazon Elastic IP]]\nAmazon's elastic IP address feature is similar to static IP address in traditional data centers, with one key difference. A user can programmatically map an elastic IP address to any virtual machine instance without a network administrator's help and without having to wait for DNS to propagate the binding. In this sense an Elastic IP Address belongs to the account and not to a virtual machine instance. It exists until it is explicitly removed, and remains associated with the account even while it is associated with no instance.\n\n===Amazon CloudWatch===\n[[File:AWS Simple Icons Monitoring Amazon CloudWatch Alarm.svg|70px|right|Amazon CloudWatch]]\nAmazon CloudWatch is a web service that provides real-time monitoring to Amazon's EC2 customers on their resource utilization such as CPU, disk, network and replica lag for RDS Database replicas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/USER_ReadRepl.html|title=Working with Read Replicas of MariaDB, MySQL, and PostgreSQL DB Instances - Amazon Relational Database Service|website=docs.aws.amazon.com}}</ref> CloudWatch does not provide any memory, disk space, or load average metrics without running additional software on the instance. Since December 2017 Amazon provides a CloudWatch Agent for Windows and Linux operating systems included disk and previously not available memory information,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Amazon CloudWatch introduces a new CloudWatch Agent with AWS Systems Manager Integration for Unified Metrics and Logs Collection|date=14 December 2017||accessdate=2 March 2020|website=aws.amazon.com|url=https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/whats-new/2017/12/amazon-cloudwatch-introduces-a-new-cloudwatch-agent-with-aws-systems-manager-integration-for-unified-metrics-and-logs-collection/}}</ref> previously Amazon provided example scripts for Linux instances to collect OS information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/mon-scripts.html|title=Monitoring Memory and Disk Metrics for Amazon EC2 Linux Instances - Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud|website=docs.aws.amazon.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://forums.aws.amazon.com/profile.jspa?userID=202407|title=AWS Developer Forums: User Profile for Henry@AWS|website=forums.aws.amazon.com}}</ref> The data is aggregated and provided through AWS management console. It can also be accessed through command line tools and Web API's<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gorillastack.com/news/cloudtrail-vs-cloudwatch/|title=GorillaStack CloudWatch vs CloudTrail|last=|first=|date=2019-09-17|website=GorillaStack|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, if the customer desires to monitor their EC2 resources through their enterprise monitoring software. Amazon provides an API which allows to operate on CloudWatch alarms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/APIReference/Welcome.html|title=Welcome - Amazon CloudWatch|website=docs.aws.amazon.com}}</ref>\n\nThe metrics collected by Amazon CloudWatch enables the [[Amazon Auto-scaling|auto-scaling]] feature to dynamically add or remove EC2 instances.{{sfnp|AWS in Action|Wittig|2016|pages= 372\u2013375 }} The customers are charged by the number of monitoring instances.\n\nSince May 2011, Amazon CloudWatch accepts custom metrics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/releasenotes/item/|title=AWS Release Notes|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.}}</ref> that can be submitted programmatically via Web Services API and then monitored the same way as all other internal metrics, including setting up the alarms for them, and since July 2014 Cloudwatch Logs service is also available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/whats-new/2014/07/10/introducing-amazon-cloudwatch-logs/|title=Introducing Amazon CloudWatch Logs|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.}}</ref>\n\nBasic Amazon CloudWatch is included in [https://aws.amazon.com/free/?all-free-tier.sort-by=item.additionalFields.SortRank&all-free-tier.sort-order=asc Amazon Free Tier] service.\n\n===Automated scaling===\n[[File:AWS Simple Icons Compute Amazon Elastic MapReduce Auto Scaling.svg|right|70px|Auto-scaling]]\n{{Further|autoscaling}}\nAmazon's auto-scaling feature of EC2 allows it to automatically adapt computing capacity to site traffic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/|title=AWS Auto Scaling|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref> The schedule-based (e.g. time-of-the-day) and rule-based (e.g. CPU utilization thresholds) auto scaling mechanisms are easy to use and efficient for simple applications. However, one potential problem is that VMs may take up to several minutes to be ready to use, which are not suitable for time critical applications. The VM startup time are dependent on image size, VM type, data center locations, etc.<ref name=\"vmstartuptime2012\">{{cite journal|last=Mao|first=Ming|author2=M. Humphrey|title=A Performance Study on the VM Startup Time in the Cloud|journal=Proceedings of 2012 IEEE 5th International Conference on Cloud Computing (Cloud2012)|year=2012|doi=10.1109/CLOUD.2012.103|isbn=978-1-4673-2892-0|page=423}}</ref>\n\n<!--===Lack of IPv6-support===\nDespite an announcement in the year 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/de/blogs/aws/elastic-load-balancing-ipv6-zone-apex-support-additional-security/|title=Elastic Load Balancing \u2013 IPv6, Zone Apex Support, Additional Security|publisher=Amazon}}</ref> EC2 doesn't yet support IPv6.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forums.aws.amazon.com/message.jspa?messageID=613158|title=AWS Developer Forums: When will IPv6 be available for ...|website=forums.aws.amazon.com}}</ref>\n-->== Pricing ==\n[[File:Amazon EC2 AWS pricing compared to similar services 1.jpg|alt=LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX BELOW 16 ( < 2CPU, 8GB RAM)|thumb|500x500px|LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX BELOW 16 ( < 2CPU, 8GB RAM)]]\n[[File:Amazon EC2 AWS pricing compared to similar services 2.jpg|alt=LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX 16 - 1040 (2CPU, 8GB RAM - 16CPU, 65GB RAM)|thumb|500x500px|LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX 16 - 1040 (2CPU, 8GB RAM - 16CPU, 65GB RAM)]]\n[[File:Amazon EC2 AWS pricing compared to similar services 3.jpg|alt=LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX ABOVE 1040 ( > 16CPU, 65GB RAM)|thumb|500x500px|LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX ABOVE 1040 ( > 16CPU, 65GB RAM)]]\nGenerally, Amazon EC2 priced on per instance / per hour basis. However, any instance can be rented on per month basis as well. In such case, Reserved and Spot Instances pricing can be applied resulting in significant discount. Instances are priced depending on their \"size\", namely how much CPU and RAM included.\n\nAmazon EC2 price varies from $2.5 per month for \"nano\" instance with 1 vCPU and 0.5 GB RAM on board to \"xlarge\" type of instances with 32 vCPU and 488 GB RAM billed up to $3997.19 per month.\n\nThe charts above show how Amazon EC2 pricing is compared to similar Cloud Computing services: Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, Kamatera, and Vultr.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://5best.cloud/aws-vs-azure-vs-google-cloud/|title=Amazon AWS vs Microsoft Azure vs Google Cloud vs Kamatera vs Vultr - 5 Best Cloud Services|date=2017-12-02|work=5 Best Cloud Services|access-date=2017-12-24|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+Amazon EC2 compared to similar cloud computing services \n|\n|Amazon EC2\n|Microsoft Azure\n|Google Cloud Platform\n|Kamatera\n|Vultr\n|-\n|1vCPU 0.5GB RAM\n|$3.29\n|\n|\n|\n| $2.5\n|-\n|1vCPU 0.75GB RAM\n|\n|$14.88\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1vCPU 1GB RAM\n| $6.83\n|\n|\n| $11\n| $5\n|-\n|1vCPU 1.75GB RAM\n|\n| $44.64\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1vCPU 2GB RAM\n| $13.14\n|\n|\n| $17\n| $10\n|-\n|1vCPU 3.75GB RAM\n|\n|\n| $24.27\n|\n|\n|-\n|2vCPU 3.5GB RAM\n|\n| $89.88\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|2vCPU 4GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n| $41\n| $20\n|-\n|2vCPU 7.5GB RAM \n|\n|\n| $48.55\n|\n|\n|-\n|2vCPU 8GB RAM\n| $52.56\n|\n|\n| $61\n|\n|-\n|4vCPU 7GB RAM\n|\n|$178.56\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|4vCPU 8GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$86\n|$40\n|-\n|4vCPU 15GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$97.09\n|\n|\n|-\n|4vCPU 15GB RAM\n|$134\n|\n|\n|$134\n|\n|-\n|6vCPU 16GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$159\n|$80\n|-\n|8vCPU 14GB RAM\n|\n|$357.12\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 16GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$184\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 30GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$194.18\n|\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 32GB RAM\n|$219.64\n|\n|\n|$280\n|$160\n|-\n|8vCPU 49GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$328\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 56GB RAM\n|\n|$744\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 32GB RAM\n|$412.53\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 65GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$408\n|\n|-\n|12vCPU 65GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$626\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 32GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$388.36\n|$746\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 65GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$320\n|-\n|20vCPU 65GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$826\n|-\n|12vCPU 112GB RAM\n|\n|$1339.20\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 112GB RAM\n|\n|$1450.80\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|20vCPU 98GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$986\n|-\n|36vCPU 60GB RAM\n|$825.06\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|20vCPU 131GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$1146\n|-\n|32vCPU 120GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$776.72\n|\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 224GB RAM\n|\n|$1935.1\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|20vCPU 196GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$1466\n|-\n|20vCPU 262GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$1786\n|-\n|24vCPU 224GB RAM\n|\n|$2678.40\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|64vCPU 240GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$1553.44\n|\n|\n|-\n|32vCPU 488GB RAM\n|$3997.19\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Reliability==\nTo make EC2 more [[Fault-tolerant system|fault-tolerant]], Amazon engineered ''Availability Zones'' that are designed to be insulated from failures in other availability zones. Availability zones do not share the same infrastructure. Applications running in more than one availability zone can achieve higher availability.<ref name=\"AWS in Action, Availability Zones\" />\n\nEC2 provides users with control over the geographical location of instances that allows for latency optimization and high levels of redundancy. For example, to minimize downtime, a user can set up server instances in multiple zones that are insulated from each other for most causes of failure such that one backs up the other.\n\nHigher-availability database services, like [[Amazon Relational Database Service]] run separately from EC2 instances.\n\n==Issues==\nIn early July 2008, the anti-spam organizations [[Outblaze]] and [[Spamhaus.org]] began blocking Amazon's EC2 address pool due to problems with the distribution of [[Spam (electronic)|spam]] and [[malware]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://blog.washingtonpost.com/securityfix/2008/07/amazon_hey_spammers_get_off_my.html\n |title=Amazon: Hey Spammers, Get Off My Cloud!\n |first=Brian\n |last=Krebs\n |authorlink=Brian Krebs\n |work=Security Fix\n |publisher=[[The Washington Post]]\n |date=July 1, 2008\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203081807/http://blog.washingtonpost.com/securityfix/2008/07/amazon_hey_spammers_get_off_my.html\n |archivedate=December 3, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nOn December 1, 2010, Amazon pulled its service to [[WikiLeaks]] after coming under political pressure in the US.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/dec/01/wikileaks-website-cables-servers-amazon | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Ewen | last=MacAskill | title=WikiLeaks website pulled by Amazon after US political pressure | date=December 2, 2010}}</ref> The Internet group [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] attempted to attack EC2 in revenge; however, Amazon was not affected by the attack.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Matthew |last1=Weaver |first2=Mark |last2=Tran |title=WikiLeaks cables: Shell, Operation Payback and Assange for the Nobel prize{{snd}}as it happened |url= https://www.theguardian.com/news/blog/2010/dec/09/wikileaks-us-embassy-cables-live-updates |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= December 9, 2010 |accessdate= May 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAmazon's websites were temporarily offline on December 12, 2010, although it was initially unclear if this was due to attacks or a hardware failure. An Amazon official later stated that it was due to a hardware failure.<ref>{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Arthur |title=Amazon says outage in Europe due to hardware failure, not hacking attack |url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/blog/2010/dec/13/amazon-failure-not-hacking-wikileaks |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= December 13, 2010 |accessdate= May 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{{wikinews|Amazon server outage affects Reddit, other websites}}\nShortly before 5&nbsp;am ET on April 21, 2011, an outage started at EC2's [[Northern Virginia]] data center that brought down several websites, including [[Foursquare City Guide|Foursquare]], [[Springpad]], [[Reddit]], [[Quora]], and [[Hootsuite]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/2011/04/21/technology/amazon_server_outage/index.htm | work=[[CNN]] | first=Julianne | last=Pepitone | title=Amazon EC2 outage downs Reddit, Quora | date=April 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/23/technology/23cloud.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | first=Steve | last=Lohr | title=Amazon Malfunction Raises Doubts About Cloud Computing | date=April 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.doeswhat.com/2011/04/21/cloud-storm-amazons-ec2-takes-down-startups/ | work=DoesWhat | title=Cloud storm, EC2 startup takedown | date=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Specifically, attempts to use Amazon's elastic-disk and database services hung, failed, or were slow. Service was restored to some parts of the datacenter (three of four \"availability zones\" in Amazon's terms) by late afternoon Eastern time that day;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://status.aws.amazon.com/,|title=6:18&nbsp;pm PDT April 21, 2011, entry, says \"all Availability Zones except one have been functioning normally for the past 5 hours.\"|website=amazon.com}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Problems in cloudflare Affect Amazon and discord.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.techgrits.com/problems-in-cloudflare-affect-sites-like-google-amazon-and-discord/,|title=April 5 entry.|website=techgrits.com}}{{date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> 0.07% of EBS volumes in one zone have also been lost; EBS failures were a part of normal operation even before this outage and were a risk documented by Amazon,<ref>[http://aws.amazon.com/ebs/ Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS)] section \"Volume Durability\"</ref> though the number of failures and the number of ''simultaneous'' failures may find some EC2 users unprepared.\n\nOn Sunday August 6, 2011, Amazon suffered a power outage in one of their Ireland availability zones.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jack | last=Clark | url=http://www.zdnet.co.uk/news/cloud/2011/08/08/lightning-strikes-amazons-european-cloud-40093641/ | title=Lightning strikes Amazon's European cloud | work=[[ZDNet]] | date=August 8, 2011}}</ref> Lightning was originally blamed for the outage; however, on August 11, Irish energy supplier ESB Networks dismissed this as a cause, but at time of writing, could not confirm what the cause of the problem was.<ref>{{cite news | first=Paul | last=Kunert | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/08/11/esb_web_outage/ | title=Amazon web outage not caused by lightning | work=[[The Register]] | date=August 11, 2011}}</ref> The power outage raised multiple questions regarding Amazon's EBS infrastructure, which caused several bugs in their software to be exposed. The bugs resulted in some customers' data being deleted when recovering EBS volumes in a mid-write operation during the crash.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jack | last=Clark | url=http://www.zdnet.co.uk/news/cloud/2011/08/10/aws-cloud-accidentally-deletes-customer-data-40093665/ | title=AWS cloud accidentally deletes customer data | work=[[ZDNet]] | date=August 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAugust 8, 2011 saw another network connectivity outage of Amazon's Northern Virginia datacenter, knocking out the likes of Reddit, Quora, Netflix and FourSquare.<ref>{{cite news | first=Steven | last=Musil | url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1023_3-20089866-93/amazon-cloud-outage-downs-netflix-quora/ | title=Amazon cloud outage downs Netflix, Quora | work= [[CNET]] | date=August 9, 2011}}</ref> The outage lasted around 25 minutes.\n\nAnother Northern Virginia datacenter outage occurred on October 22, 2012, from approximately 10&nbsp;am to 4&nbsp;pm PT. Edmodo, Airbnb, Flipboard, Reddit, and other customers were affected. Anonymous claimed responsibility, however Amazon denied this assertion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tibken |first=Shara | url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1023_3-57537499-93/amazon-cloud-outage-impacts-reddit-airbnb-flipboard/ | title=Amazon cloud outage impacts Reddit, Airbnb, Flipboard | date=October 22, 2012 |work=[[CNET]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Amazon Virtual Private Cloud]]\n* [[Alibaba Cloud ECS]]\n* [[AppScale]]\n* [[Bitnami]]\n* [[CopperEgg]]\n* [[ElasticHosts]]\n* [[Eucalyptus (computing)]]\n* [[FlexiScale]]\n* [[FUJITSU Cloud IaaS Trusted Public S5]]\n* [[GoGrid]]\n* [[Google App Engine]]\n* [[Google Cloud Platform]]\n* [[GreenQloud]]\n* [[Internap]]\n* [[Linode]]\n* [[Lunacloud]]\n* [[Microsoft Azure]]\n* [[Nimbula]]\n* [[OpenShift]]\n* [[Oracle Cloud]]\n* [[OrionVM]]\n* [[OVH]]\n* [[Rackspace Cloud]]\n* [[RightScale]]\n* [[Savvis]]\n* [[TurnKey Linux Virtual Appliance Library]]\n* [[Zadara Storage]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"AWS in Action, Availability Zones\" >{{Cite book\n|title=Amazon Web Services in Action\n|last=Wittig |first=Andreas\n|last2=Wittig |first2=Michael\n|year=2016\n|publisher=Manning Press\n|isbn=978-1-61729-288-0\n|ref={{harvid|AWS in Action|Wittig|2016}}\n|pages=290\u2013294\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n* {{official website|https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/}}\n\n{{Amazon}}\n{{Cloud computing}}\n\n[[Category:Amazon Web Services|EC2]]\n[[Category:Cloud computing]]\n[[Category:Cloud computing providers]]\n[[Category:Cloud infrastructure]]\n[[Category:Cloud platforms]]\n[[Category:Web services]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=July 2014}}\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2)\n| logo                   = [[File:AWS Simple Icons Compute Amazon EC2 Instances.svg|200px]]\n| logo caption           = Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2)\n| screenshot             = <!-- [[File: ]] -->\n| caption                = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = Amazon.com, Inc.\n| developer              = [[Amazon.com]]\n| released               = {{Start date and age|2006|08|25}} (public beta)\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest preview version = \n| status                 = Active\n| programming language   = \n| operating system       = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Linux]]\n* [[Microsoft Windows]]\n* [[FreeBSD]]\n}}\n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = English\n| genre                  = [[Virtual private server]]\n| license                = [[Proprietary software]]\n| alexa                  = \n| website                = {{URL|https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/}}\n}}\n\n'''Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud''' ('''EC2''') forms a central part of [[Amazon.com]]'s [[cloud-computing]] platform, [[Amazon Web Services]] (AWS), by allowing users to rent [[virtual computer]]s on which to run their own computer applications. EC2 encourages scalable deployment of applications by providing a [[web service]] through which a user can boot an [[Amazon Machine Image]] (AMI) to configure a [[Virtual Machine|virtual machine]], which Amazon calls an \"instance\", containing any software desired. A user can create, launch, and terminate [[Server (computing)|server]]-instances as needed, paying by the second for active servers{{snd}}hence the term \"elastic\". EC2 provides users with control over the geographical location of instances that allows for [[latency (disambiguation)|latency]] optimization and high levels of [[Redundancy (engineering)|redundancy]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.news.com/8301-10784_3-9904091-7.html\n |title=Amazon Web Services adds 'resiliency' to EC2 compute service\n |first=Martin\n |last=LaMonica\n |work=[[CNET]]\n |date=March 27, 2008\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, Amazon switched its own retail website to use EC2 and AWS.<ref>\n{{Cite AV media|title=AWS Cloud Tour 2011 {{!}} Australia: Event Highlights|URL=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uf07L1RUOW4|medium=video}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{see also|Timeline of Amazon Web Services}}\nAmazon announced a limited public beta test of EC2 on August 25, 2006,<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2006/08/amazon_ec2_beta.html\n |title=Amazon EC2 Beta\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=August 25, 2006\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate= May 31, 2013\n}}</ref> offering access on a first-come, first-served basis.\nAmazon added two new instance types (Large and Extra-Large) on October 16, 2007.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2007/10/amazon-ec2-gets.html\n |title=Amazon EC2 Gets More Muscle\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=October 16, 2007\n}}</ref> On May 29, 2008, two more types were added, High-CPU Medium and High-CPU Extra Large.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/05/more-ec2-power.html\n |title=More EC2 power\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=May 29, 2008\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}</ref> There were twelve types of instances available.<ref>[http://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/ Amazon EC2 Instances]. Aws.amazon.com. Retrieved on 2013-08-09.</ref>\n\nAmazon added three new features on March 27, 2008,<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/03/new-ec2-feature.html\n |title=New EC2 Features\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=March 27, 2008\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}</ref> static IP addresses, availability zones, and user selectable kernels.\nOn August 20, 2008, Amazon added [[Elastic Block Store]] (EBS)<ref name=\"ebs\">{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/08/amazon-elastic.html\n |title=Amazon EBS (Elastic Block Store) - Bring Us Your Data\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date= August 20, 2008\n |accessdate= May 31, 2013\n |work= Amazon Web Services Blog\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110328011236/http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/08/amazon-elastic.html| archivedate= March 28, 2011 |url-status= live}}</ref>\nThis provides persistent storage, a feature that had been lacking since the service was introduced.\n\nAmazon EC2 went into full production when it dropped the beta label on October 23, 2008. On the same day, Amazon announced the following features:<ref name=\"BigDayForEC2\">{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2008/10/big-day-for-ec2.html\n |title=Big Day For EC2\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=August 23, 2008\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}</ref>\na service level agreement for EC2,\n[[Microsoft Windows]] in beta form on EC2,\n[[Microsoft SQL Server]] in beta form on EC2,\nplans for an AWS management console, and\nplans for load balancing, autoscaling, and cloud monitoring services.<ref name=\"BigDayForEC2\"/> These features were subsequently added on May 18, 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2009/05/new-aws-load-balancing-automatic-scaling-and-cloud-monitoring-services.html\n |title=New Features for EC2\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |date=May 18, 2009\n |work=Amazon Web Services Blog\n |accessdate=August 1, 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nAmazon EC2 was developed mostly by a team in [[Cape Town, South Africa]] led by Chris Pinkham.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://itknowledgeexchange.techtarget.com/cloud-computing/2010/06/17/amazons-early-efforts-at-cloud-computing-partly-accidental/\n|title=Amazon's early efforts at cloud computing? Partly accidental\n|date=June 17, 2010}}</ref>\nPinkham provided the initial architecture guidance for EC2 and then built the team and led the development of the project along with [[Willem van Biljon]].\n\n==Instance types==\nInitially, EC2 used [[Xen]] virtualization exclusively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citrix.com/global-partners/amazon-web-services.html |title=Citrix and Amazon Web Services (AWS) |date= |publisher=citrix.com |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> However, on November 6, 2017, Amazon announced<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/now-available-compute-intensive-c5-instances-for-amazon-ec2/ |title=Now Available \u2013 Compute-Intensive C5 Instances for Amazon EC2|date= |accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref> the new C5 family of instances that were based on a custom architecture around the [[Kernel-based Virtual Machine|KVM hypervisor]], called Nitro.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/faqs/#compute-optimized |title=Amazon EC2 FAQs |date= |accessdate=November 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o9_4uGvbvnk |title=AWS re:Invent 2017: NEW LAUNCH! Amazon EC2 Bare Metal Instances (CMP330)|date=|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Each virtual machine, called an \"instance\", functions as a [[virtual private server]]. Amazon sizes instances based on \"Elastic Compute Units\". The performance of otherwise identical virtual machines may vary.<ref>J. Dejun, G. Pierre and C.-H. Chi. [http://www.globule.org/publi/EPARPSOA_nfpsla2009.html EC2 Performance Analysis for Resource Provisioning of Service-Oriented Applications]. In Proceedings of the Workshop on Non-Functional Properties and SLA Management in Service-Oriented Computing, November 2009.</ref> On November 28, 2017, AWS announced a bare-metal instance type offering marking a remarkable departure from exclusively offering virtualized instance types.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/28/aws-launches-bare-metal-instances/ |title=AWS launches bare metal instances |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |date=November 28, 2017 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2019, the following instance types were offered:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/|title=Amazon EC2 Instance Types \u2013 Amazon Web Services (AWS)|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-28}}</ref>\n* General Purpose: A1, T3, T2, M5, M5a, M4, T3a\n* Compute Optimized: C5, C5n, C4\n* Memory Optimized: R5, R5a, R4, X1e, X1, High Memory, z1d\n* Accelerated Computing: P3, P2, G3, F1\n* Storage Optimized: H1, I3, D2\n{{As of |April 2018}}, the following paying method for instance were offered:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aws.amazon.com/ec2/pricing/ |title=Amazon EC2 Pricing |date= |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n* On-demand: pay by the hour without commitment.\n* Reserved: rent instances with one-time payment receiving discounts on the hourly charge.\n* Spot: bid-based service: runs the jobs only if the spot price is below the bid specified by bidder. The spot price is claimed to be supply-demand based, however a 2011 study concluded that the price was generally not set to clear the market, but was dominated by an undisclosed [[reserve price]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/users/wwwb/cgi-bin/tr-info.cgi/2011/CS/CS-2011-09 |title=Technical Report CS-2011-09 |publisher=cs.technion.ac.il |date= |accessdate=December 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Cost===\n[[File:AmazonWebServicesPriceReductions.JPG|thumb|Amazon CTO Werner Vogels announces price reductions at AWS Summit 2013 NYC]]\n{{As of |2018|04}}, Amazon charged about $0.0058/hour ($4.176/month) for the smallest \"Nano Instance\" (t2.nano) virtual machine running Linux or Windows. Storage-optimized instances cost as much as $4.992/hour (i3.16xlarge). \"Reserved\" instances can go as low as $2.50/month for a three-year prepaid plan.<ref group=\"note\">$109 for a three-year Heavy Utilization Reserved t2.micro Instances reservation amortized over thirty-six months plus one month at $0.002/hour.</ref><ref>[http://aws.amazon.com/ec2/#pricing Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2), Cloud Computing Servers]. Aws.amazon.com (2014-07-01). Retrieved on 2014-07-01.</ref> The data transfer charge ranges from free to $0.12 per gigabyte, depending on the direction and monthly volume (inbound data transfer is free on all AWS services<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2011/06/aws-lowers-its-pricing-again-free-inbound-data-transfer-and-lower-outbound-data-transfer-for-all-ser.html\n |title=AWS Lowers its Pricing Again!&nbsp;\u2013 No Inbound Data Transfer Fees and Lower Outbound Data Transfer for All Services including Amazon CloudFront\n |first=Jeff\n |last=Barr\n |work=[[Typepad]]\n |date=June 29, 2011\n|accessdate=July 6, 2011\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110707085314/http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2011/06/aws-lowers-its-pricing-again-free-inbound-data-transfer-and-lower-outbound-data-transfer-for-all-ser.html| archivedate= July 7, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>).\n\n===Free tier===\n{{As of|2010|December}} Amazon offered a bundle of free resource credits to new account holders. The credits are designed to run a \"micro\" sized server, storage (EBS), and bandwidth for one year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/free/|title=AWS Free Tier|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.}}</ref> Unused credits cannot be carried over from one month to the next.<ref>{{Cite web|title = FAQs|url = http://aws.amazon.com/free/faqs/|website = Amazon Web Services, Inc.|accessdate = 2015-07-31}}</ref>\n\n===Reserved Instances===\nReserved instances enable EC2 or RDS service users to reserve an instance for one or three years. The corresponding hourly rate charged by Amazon to operate the instance is 35-75% lower than the rate charged for on-demand instances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2011/12/reserved-instance-options-for-amazon-ec2.html|title=Additional Reserved Instance Options for Amazon EC2|publisher=Amazon}}</ref>\nReserved Instances can be purchased in three different ways: All Upfront, Partial Upfront and No Upfront. The different purchase options allow for different structuring of payment models.\nIn September 2016, AWS announced several enhancements to Reserved Instances, introducing a new feature called scope and a new reservation type called a Convertible.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cloudhealthtech.com/blog/quick-start-guide-aws-regional-convertible-reservations |title=A Quick Start Guide To AWS Regional & Convertible Reservations |publisher=[[CloudHealth Technologies]] |first= Alan |last=Santos |date=September 29, 2016 |access-date=2016-10-04}}</ref> In October 2017, AWS announced the allowance to subdivide the instances purchased for more flexibility <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/3180821/cloud-computing/aws-follows-google-with-reserved-instance-flexibility-changes.html |title=AWS Follows Google With Reserved Instance Flexibility Changes |first=Blair |last=Hanley Frank |work=[[PC World]] |date=March 14, 2017 |access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref>\n\n===Spot Instances===\nCloud providers maintain large amounts of excess capacity they have to sell or risk incurring losses.<ref name=\"ladypine\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cs.technion.ac.il/~ladypine/spotprice-ieee.pdf|title=Deconstructing Amazon EC2 Spot Instance Pricing|last=Technion - Israel Institute of Technology|date=|publisher=Technion University |access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref>\nAmazon EC2 Spot instances are spare compute capacity in the AWS cloud available at up to 90% discount compared to On-Demand prices. As a trade-off, AWS offers no [[Service-level agreement|SLA]] on these instances and customers take the risk that it can be interrupted with only two minutes of notification when Amazon needs the capacity back. Researchers from the Israeli Institute of Technology found that \"they (Spot instances) are typically generated at random from within a tight price interval via a dynamic hidden reserve price\".<ref name=\"ladypine\" /> Some companies, like Spotinst, are using big data combined with machine learning to predict spot interruptions up to 15 minutes in advance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thenewstack.io/spotinst-making-cheaper-excess-compute-capacity/ |title=Spotinst: Making the Most of Cheaper Excess Compute Capacity |first=Susan |last=Hall |date=December 26, 2017 |work=The News Stack |access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/25/spotnist-delivers-spot-cloud-infrastructure-services-at-discount-prices/|title=Spotinst delivers spot cloud infrastructure services at discount prices|last=Miller |first=Ron |date=October 25, 2017 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=2018-03-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Savings Plans ===\nIn November 2019, Amazon announced Savings Plans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/savingsplans/|title=New \u2013 Savings Plans for AWS Compute Services|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Savings Plans are an alternative to Reserved Instances<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gorillastack.com/news/aws-savings-plans-reserved-instances/|title=Savings Plans vs Reserved Instances|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> that come in 2 different plan types: Compute Savings Plans and EC2 Instances Savings Plans. Compute Savings Plans allow an organisation to commit to EC2 and Fargate usage with the freedom to change region, family, size, availability zone, OS and tenancy inside the lifespan of the commitment. EC2 Instance Savings plans provide the lowest prices but are less flexible meaning a user must commit to individual instance families within a region to take advantage, but with the freedom to change instances within the family in that region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/savingsplans/faq/|title=AWS Savings Plans FAQ|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\n\n===Operating systems===\n{{Further|operating system}}\nWhen it launched in August 2006, the EC2 service offered [[Linux]] and later [[Sun Microsystems]]' [[OpenSolaris]] and [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris Express Community Edition]]. In October 2008, EC2 added the [[Windows Server 2003]] and [[Windows Server 2008]] operating systems to the list of available [[operating system]]s.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17939_109-10073696-2.html\n |title=Amazon's Linux cloud computing out of beta, joined by Windows\n |first=Stephen\n |last=Shankland\n |work=[[CNET]]\n |date=October 23, 2008\n|accessdate=October 24, 2008\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.amazon.com/windows/\n |title=Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) Running Microsoft Windows Server and SQL Server\n |date=October 23, 2008\n|accessdate=October 25, 2008\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081201023846/http://aws.amazon.com/windows/| archivedate= 1 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\nIn March 2011, [[NetBSD]] AMIs became available.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.netbsd.org/tnf/entry/netbsd_now_runs_under_amazon |title=NetBSD now runs under Amazon EC2 |first=Jean-Yves |last=Migeon |work=NetBSD Blog |date=March 13, 2011 |accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> In November 2012, [[Windows Server 2012]] support was added.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2012/11/windows-server-2012-now-available-on-aws.html\n |title=Windows Server 2012 Now Available on AWS\n |date=November 19, 2012\n|accessdate=March 26, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nSince 2006, Colin Percival, a FreeBSD developer and Security Officer, solicited Amazon to add FreeBSD.<ref name=\"YT interview\">{{cite web|last1=Barr|first1=Jeff|title=Interview - Live from AWS re:Invent Colin Percival, FreeBSD Developer|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SK7EeV_GD3M|publisher=Amazon Web Services 28.11.2012|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> In November 2012, Amazon officially supported running [[FreeBSD]] in EC2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aws.typepad.com/aws/2012/11/aws-marketplace-additional-operating-system-support.html|title=AWS Marketplace \u2013 Additional EC2 Operating System Support (FreeBSD, Debian, CentOS)|publisher=Amazon}}</ref><ref name=CP-FreeBSDonEC2HowTo>{{cite web|last1=Percival|first1=Colin|title=How to build FreeBSD/EC2 images|url=http://www.daemonology.net/blog/2014-02-16-FreeBSD-EC2-build.html|publisher=Colin Percival|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=CP-FreeBSD-EC2>{{cite web|last1=Percival|first1=Colin|title=FreeBSD on EC2|url=http://www.daemonology.net/freebsd-on-ec2/|publisher=Colin Percival|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> The FreeBSD/EC2 platform is maintained by Percival<ref name=AWS-ColinPercival>{{cite web|title=Colin Percival|url=https://aws.amazon.com/marketplace/seller-profile?id=4a931b8a-95f6-4bb2-8b7e-53507851c459|website=awsmarketplace|publisher=Amazon Web Services, Inc.|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref> who also developed the secure [[Data deduplication|deduplicating]] [[Amazon S3]]-cloud based backup service [[Tarsnap]].<ref name=TarsnapCP>{{cite web|last1=Percival|first1=Colin|title=About Tarsnap|url=http://www.tarsnap.com/about.html|publisher=Tarsnap and C. Percival|accessdate=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmazon has their own Linux distribution based on the [[Fedora (operating system)|Fedora]] and [[Red Hat Enterprise Linux]] as a low cost offering known as the [[Amazon Machine Image|Amazon Linux AMI]]. Version 2013.03 included:<ref>{{cite web |title= Amazon Linux AMI 2013.03 Release Notes |work= AWS web site |url= http://aws.amazon.com/amazon-linux-ami/2013.03-release-notes/ |accessdate= May 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n* [[Linux kernel]] version 3.4.34\n* Java [[OpenJDK]] Runtime Environment (IcedTea6 1.11.4)\n* [[GNU Compiler Collection]] gcc.x86_64 4.4.6-3.45.amzn1\n\n===Persistent storage===\nAn EC2 instance may be launched with a choice of two types of storage for its boot disk or \"root device.\" The first option is a local \"instance-store\" disk as a root device (originally the only choice). The second option is to use an EBS volume as a root device. Instance-store volumes are temporary storage, which survive rebooting an EC2 instance, but when the instance is stopped or terminated (e.g., by an API call, or due to a failure), this store is lost.\n\nThe [[Amazon Elastic Block Store]] (EBS) provides raw [[block devices]] that can be attached to Amazon EC2 instances. These block devices can then be used like any raw block device. In a typical use case, this would include formatting the device with a [[filesystem]] and [[mounting (computing)|mounting]] it. In addition, EBS supports a number of advanced storage features, including snapshotting and cloning. EBS volumes can be up to 16TB in size. EBS volumes are built on replicated storage, so that the failure of a single component will not cause data loss.\nEBS was introduced to the general public by Amazon in August 2008.<ref name=\"ebs\" />\n\n[[File:AWS Simple Icons Storage Amazon EBS.svg|right|70px|Amazon EBS]]\nEBS volumes provide persistent storage independent of the lifetime of the EC2 instance, and act much like hard drives on a real server. More accurately, they appear as block devices to the operating system that are backed by Amazon's disk arrays. The OS is free to use the device however it wants. In the most common case, a file system is loaded and the volume acts as a hard drive. Another possible use is the creation of RAID arrays by combining two or more EBS volumes. RAID allows increases of speed and/or reliability of EBS. Users can set up and manage storage volumes of sizes from 1GB to 16TB. The volumes support snapshots, which can be taken from a GUI tool or the API. EBS volumes can be attached or detached from instances while they are running, and moved from one instance to another.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://1201restart.com/Articles/Introduction_to_EBS_Volumes\n |title        = Introduction to EBS Volumes\n |publisher    = 1201 Restart.com\n |date         = December 2010\n |accessdate   = December 18, 2010\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110513114653/http://1201restart.com/Articles/Introduction_to_EBS_Volumes\n |archive-date = 2011-05-13\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n[[Amazon S3|Simple Storage Service (S3)]] is a storage system in which data is accessible to EC2 instances, or directly over the network to suitably authenticated callers (all communication is over HTTP). Amazon does not charge for the bandwidth for communications between EC2 instances and S3 storage \"in the same region.\" Accessing S3 data stored in a different region (for example, data stored in Europe from a US East Coast EC2 instance) will be billed at Amazon's normal rates.\n\nS3-based storage is priced per gigabyte per month. Applications access S3 through an API. For example, [[Hadoop|Apache Hadoop]] supports a special s3: filesystem to support reading from and writing to S3 storage during a [[MapReduce]] job. There are also S3 filesystems for Linux, which mount a remote S3 filestore on an EC2 image, as if it were local storage. As S3 is not a full [[POSIX]] filesystem, things may not behave the same as on a local disk (e.g., no locking support).\n\n===Elastic IP addresses===\n[[File:AWS Simple Icons Compute Amazon EC2 Elastic IP.svg|70px|right|Amazon Elastic IP]]\nAmazon's elastic IP address feature is similar to static IP address in traditional data centers, with one key difference. A user can programmatically map an elastic IP address to any virtual machine instance without a network administrator's help and without having to wait for DNS to propagate the binding. In this sense an Elastic IP Address belongs to the account and not to a virtual machine instance. It exists until it is explicitly removed, and remains associated with the account even while it is associated with no instance.\n\n===Amazon CloudWatch===\n[[File:AWS Simple Icons Monitoring Amazon CloudWatch Alarm.svg|70px|right|Amazon CloudWatch]]\nAmazon CloudWatch is a web service that provides real-time monitoring to Amazon's EC2 customers on their resource utilization such as CPU, disk, network and replica lag for RDS Database replicas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/USER_ReadRepl.html|title=Working with Read Replicas of MariaDB, MySQL, and PostgreSQL DB Instances - Amazon Relational Database Service|website=docs.aws.amazon.com}}</ref> CloudWatch does not provide any memory, disk space, or load average metrics without running additional software on the instance. Since December 2017 Amazon provides a CloudWatch Agent for Windows and Linux operating systems included disk and previously not available memory information,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Amazon CloudWatch introduces a new CloudWatch Agent with AWS Systems Manager Integration for Unified Metrics and Logs Collection|date=14 December 2017||accessdate=2 March 2020|website=aws.amazon.com|url=https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/whats-new/2017/12/amazon-cloudwatch-introduces-a-new-cloudwatch-agent-with-aws-systems-manager-integration-for-unified-metrics-and-logs-collection/}}</ref> previously Amazon provided example scripts for Linux instances to collect OS information.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/mon-scripts.html|title=Monitoring Memory and Disk Metrics for Amazon EC2 Linux Instances - Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud|website=docs.aws.amazon.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://forums.aws.amazon.com/profile.jspa?userID=202407|title=AWS Developer Forums: User Profile for Henry@AWS|website=forums.aws.amazon.com}}</ref> The data is aggregated and provided through AWS management console. It can also be accessed through command line tools and Web API's<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gorillastack.com/news/cloudtrail-vs-cloudwatch/|title=GorillaStack CloudWatch vs CloudTrail|last=|first=|date=2019-09-17|website=GorillaStack|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, if the customer desires to monitor their EC2 resources through their enterprise monitoring software. Amazon provides an API which allows to operate on CloudWatch alarms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/APIReference/Welcome.html|title=Welcome - Amazon CloudWatch|website=docs.aws.amazon.com}}</ref>\n\nThe metrics collected by Amazon CloudWatch enables the [[Amazon Auto-scaling|auto-scaling]] feature to dynamically add or remove EC2 instances.{{sfnp|AWS in Action|Wittig|2016|pages= 372\u2013375 }} The customers are charged by the number of monitoring instances.\n\nSince May 2011, Amazon CloudWatch accepts custom metrics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/releasenotes/item/|title=AWS Release Notes|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.}}</ref> that can be submitted programmatically via Web Services API and then monitored the same way as all other internal metrics, including setting up the alarms for them, and since July 2014 Cloudwatch Logs service is also available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/about-aws/whats-new/2014/07/10/introducing-amazon-cloudwatch-logs/|title=Introducing Amazon CloudWatch Logs|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.}}</ref>\n\nBasic Amazon CloudWatch is included in [https://aws.amazon.com/free/?all-free-tier.sort-by=item.additionalFields.SortRank&all-free-tier.sort-order=asc Amazon Free Tier] service.\n\n===Automated scaling===\n[[File:AWS Simple Icons Compute Amazon Elastic MapReduce Auto Scaling.svg|right|70px|Auto-scaling]]\n{{Further|autoscaling}}\nAmazon's auto-scaling feature of EC2 allows it to automatically adapt computing capacity to site traffic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/|title=AWS Auto Scaling|website=Amazon Web Services, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref> The schedule-based (e.g. time-of-the-day) and rule-based (e.g. CPU utilization thresholds) auto scaling mechanisms are easy to use and efficient for simple applications. However, one potential problem is that VMs may take up to several minutes to be ready to use, which are not suitable for time critical applications. The VM startup time are dependent on image size, VM type, data center locations, etc.<ref name=\"vmstartuptime2012\">{{cite journal|last=Mao|first=Ming|author2=M. Humphrey|title=A Performance Study on the VM Startup Time in the Cloud|journal=Proceedings of 2012 IEEE 5th International Conference on Cloud Computing (Cloud2012)|year=2012|doi=10.1109/CLOUD.2012.103|isbn=978-1-4673-2892-0|page=423}}</ref>\n\n<!--===Lack of IPv6-support===\nDespite an announcement in the year 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aws.amazon.com/de/blogs/aws/elastic-load-balancing-ipv6-zone-apex-support-additional-security/|title=Elastic Load Balancing \u2013 IPv6, Zone Apex Support, Additional Security|publisher=Amazon}}</ref> EC2 doesn't yet support IPv6.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://forums.aws.amazon.com/message.jspa?messageID=613158|title=AWS Developer Forums: When will IPv6 be available for ...|website=forums.aws.amazon.com}}</ref>\n-->== Pricing ==\n[[File:Amazon EC2 AWS pricing compared to similar services 1.jpg|alt=LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX BELOW 16 ( < 2CPU, 8GB RAM)|thumb|500x500px|LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX BELOW 16 ( < 2CPU, 8GB RAM)]]\n[[File:Amazon EC2 AWS pricing compared to similar services 2.jpg|alt=LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX 16 - 1040 (2CPU, 8GB RAM - 16CPU, 65GB RAM)|thumb|500x500px|LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX 16 - 1040 (2CPU, 8GB RAM - 16CPU, 65GB RAM)]]\n[[File:Amazon EC2 AWS pricing compared to similar services 3.jpg|alt=LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX ABOVE 1040 ( > 16CPU, 65GB RAM)|thumb|500x500px|LINUX CLOUD HOSTING: PERFORMANCE INDEX ABOVE 1040 ( > 16CPU, 65GB RAM)]]\nGenerally, Amazon EC2 priced on per instance / per hour basis. However, any instance can be rented on per month basis as well. In such case, Reserved and Spot Instances pricing can be applied resulting in significant discount. Instances are priced depending on their \"size\", namely how much CPU and RAM included.\n\nAmazon EC2 price varies from $2.5 per month for \"nano\" instance with 1 vCPU and 0.5 GB RAM on board to \"xlarge\" type of instances with 32 vCPU and 488 GB RAM billed up to $3997.19 per month.\n\nThe charts above show how Amazon EC2 pricing is compared to similar Cloud Computing services: Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, Kamatera, and Vultr.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://5best.cloud/aws-vs-azure-vs-google-cloud/|title=Amazon AWS vs Microsoft Azure vs Google Cloud vs Kamatera vs Vultr - 5 Best Cloud Services|date=2017-12-02|work=5 Best Cloud Services|access-date=2017-12-24|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+Amazon EC2 compared to similar cloud computing services \n|\n|Amazon EC2\n|Microsoft Azure\n|Google Cloud Platform\n|Kamatera\n|Vultr\n|-\n|1vCPU 0.5GB RAM\n|$3.29\n|\n|\n|\n| $2.5\n|-\n|1vCPU 0.75GB RAM\n|\n|$14.88\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1vCPU 1GB RAM\n| $6.83\n|\n|\n| $11\n| $5\n|-\n|1vCPU 1.75GB RAM\n|\n| $44.64\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1vCPU 2GB RAM\n| $13.14\n|\n|\n| $17\n| $10\n|-\n|1vCPU 3.75GB RAM\n|\n|\n| $24.27\n|\n|\n|-\n|2vCPU 3.5GB RAM\n|\n| $89.88\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|2vCPU 4GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n| $41\n| $20\n|-\n|2vCPU 7.5GB RAM \n|\n|\n| $48.55\n|\n|\n|-\n|2vCPU 8GB RAM\n| $52.56\n|\n|\n| $61\n|\n|-\n|4vCPU 7GB RAM\n|\n|$178.56\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|4vCPU 8GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$86\n|$40\n|-\n|4vCPU 15GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$97.09\n|\n|\n|-\n|4vCPU 15GB RAM\n|$134\n|\n|\n|$134\n|\n|-\n|6vCPU 16GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$159\n|$80\n|-\n|8vCPU 14GB RAM\n|\n|$357.12\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 16GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$184\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 30GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$194.18\n|\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 32GB RAM\n|$219.64\n|\n|\n|$280\n|$160\n|-\n|8vCPU 49GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$328\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 56GB RAM\n|\n|$744\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 32GB RAM\n|$412.53\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|8vCPU 65GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$408\n|\n|-\n|12vCPU 65GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|$626\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 32GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$388.36\n|$746\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 65GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$320\n|-\n|20vCPU 65GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$826\n|-\n|12vCPU 112GB RAM\n|\n|$1339.20\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 112GB RAM\n|\n|$1450.80\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|20vCPU 98GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$986\n|-\n|36vCPU 60GB RAM\n|$825.06\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|20vCPU 131GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$1146\n|-\n|32vCPU 120GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$776.72\n|\n|\n|-\n|16vCPU 224GB RAM\n|\n|$1935.1\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|20vCPU 196GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$1466\n|-\n|20vCPU 262GB RAM\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|$1786\n|-\n|24vCPU 224GB RAM\n|\n|$2678.40\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|64vCPU 240GB RAM\n|\n|\n|$1553.44\n|\n|\n|-\n|32vCPU 488GB RAM\n|$3997.19\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Reliability==\nTo make EC2 more [[Fault-tolerant system|fault-tolerant]], Amazon engineered ''Availability Zones'' that are designed to be insulated from failures in other availability zones. Availability zones do not share the same infrastructure. Applications running in more than one availability zone can achieve higher availability.<ref name=\"AWS in Action, Availability Zones\" />\n\nEC2 provides users with control over the geographical location of instances that allows for latency optimization and high levels of redundancy. For example, to minimize downtime, a user can set up server instances in multiple zones that are insulated from each other for most causes of failure such that one backs up the other.\n\nHigher-availability database services, like [[Amazon Relational Database Service]] run separately from EC2 instances.\n\n==Issues==\nIn early July 2008, the anti-spam organizations [[Outblaze]] and [[Spamhaus.org]] began blocking Amazon's EC2 address pool due to problems with the distribution of [[Spam (electronic)|spam]] and [[malware]].<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://blog.washingtonpost.com/securityfix/2008/07/amazon_hey_spammers_get_off_my.html\n |title=Amazon: Hey Spammers, Get Off My Cloud!\n |first=Brian\n |last=Krebs\n |authorlink=Brian Krebs\n |work=Security Fix\n |publisher=[[The Washington Post]]\n |date=July 1, 2008\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203081807/http://blog.washingtonpost.com/securityfix/2008/07/amazon_hey_spammers_get_off_my.html\n |archivedate=December 3, 2013\n}}</ref>\n\nOn December 1, 2010, Amazon pulled its service to [[WikiLeaks]] after coming under political pressure in the US.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/dec/01/wikileaks-website-cables-servers-amazon | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Ewen | last=MacAskill | title=WikiLeaks website pulled by Amazon after US political pressure | date=December 2, 2010}}</ref> The Internet group [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] attempted to attack EC2 in revenge; however, Amazon was not affected by the attack.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Matthew |last1=Weaver |first2=Mark |last2=Tran |title=WikiLeaks cables: Shell, Operation Payback and Assange for the Nobel prize{{snd}}as it happened |url= https://www.theguardian.com/news/blog/2010/dec/09/wikileaks-us-embassy-cables-live-updates |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= December 9, 2010 |accessdate= May 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAmazon's websites were temporarily offline on December 12, 2010, although it was initially unclear if this was due to attacks or a hardware failure. An Amazon official later stated that it was due to a hardware failure.<ref>{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Arthur |title=Amazon says outage in Europe due to hardware failure, not hacking attack |url= https://www.theguardian.com/technology/blog/2010/dec/13/amazon-failure-not-hacking-wikileaks |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= December 13, 2010 |accessdate= May 31, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{{wikinews|Amazon server outage affects Reddit, other websites}}\nShortly before 5&nbsp;am ET on April 21, 2011, an outage started at EC2's [[Northern Virginia]] data center that brought down several websites, including [[Foursquare City Guide|Foursquare]], [[Springpad]], [[Reddit]], [[Quora]], and [[Hootsuite]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/2011/04/21/technology/amazon_server_outage/index.htm | work=[[CNN]] | first=Julianne | last=Pepitone | title=Amazon EC2 outage downs Reddit, Quora | date=April 21, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/23/technology/23cloud.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | first=Steve | last=Lohr | title=Amazon Malfunction Raises Doubts About Cloud Computing | date=April 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.doeswhat.com/2011/04/21/cloud-storm-amazons-ec2-takes-down-startups/ | work=DoesWhat | title=Cloud storm, EC2 startup takedown | date=April 21, 2011}}</ref> Specifically, attempts to use Amazon's elastic-disk and database services hung, failed, or were slow. Service was restored to some parts of the datacenter (three of four \"availability zones\" in Amazon's terms) by late afternoon Eastern time that day;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://status.aws.amazon.com/,|title=6:18&nbsp;pm PDT April 21, 2011, entry, says \"all Availability Zones except one have been functioning normally for the past 5 hours.\"|website=amazon.com}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> problems for at least some customers were continuing as of April 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://status.aws.amazon.com/,|title=April 25 entry.|website=amazon.com}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> 0.07% of EBS volumes in one zone have also been lost; EBS failures were a part of normal operation even before this outage and were a risk documented by Amazon,<ref>[http://aws.amazon.com/ebs/ Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS)] section \"Volume Durability\"</ref> though the number of failures and the number of ''simultaneous'' failures may find some EC2 users unprepared.\n\nOn Sunday August 6, 2011, Amazon suffered a power outage in one of their Ireland availability zones.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jack | last=Clark | url=http://www.zdnet.co.uk/news/cloud/2011/08/08/lightning-strikes-amazons-european-cloud-40093641/ | title=Lightning strikes Amazon's European cloud | work=[[ZDNet]] | date=August 8, 2011}}</ref> Lightning was originally blamed for the outage; however, on August 11, Irish energy supplier ESB Networks dismissed this as a cause, but at time of writing, could not confirm what the cause of the problem was.<ref>{{cite news | first=Paul | last=Kunert | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/08/11/esb_web_outage/ | title=Amazon web outage not caused by lightning | work=[[The Register]] | date=August 11, 2011}}</ref> The power outage raised multiple questions regarding Amazon's EBS infrastructure, which caused several bugs in their software to be exposed. The bugs resulted in some customers' data being deleted when recovering EBS volumes in a mid-write operation during the crash.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jack | last=Clark | url=http://www.zdnet.co.uk/news/cloud/2011/08/10/aws-cloud-accidentally-deletes-customer-data-40093665/ | title=AWS cloud accidentally deletes customer data | work=[[ZDNet]] | date=August 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAugust 8, 2011 saw another network connectivity outage of Amazon's Northern Virginia datacenter, knocking out the likes of Reddit, Quora, Netflix and FourSquare.<ref>{{cite news | first=Steven | last=Musil | url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1023_3-20089866-93/amazon-cloud-outage-downs-netflix-quora/ | title=Amazon cloud outage downs Netflix, Quora | work= [[CNET]] | date=August 9, 2011}}</ref> The outage lasted around 25 minutes.\n\nAnother Northern Virginia datacenter outage occurred on October 22, 2012, from approximately 10&nbsp;am to 4&nbsp;pm PT. Edmodo, Airbnb, Flipboard, Reddit, and other customers were affected. Anonymous claimed responsibility, however Amazon denied this assertion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tibken |first=Shara | url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1023_3-57537499-93/amazon-cloud-outage-impacts-reddit-airbnb-flipboard/ | title=Amazon cloud outage impacts Reddit, Airbnb, Flipboard | date=October 22, 2012 |work=[[CNET]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Amazon Virtual Private Cloud]]\n* [[Alibaba Cloud ECS]]\n* [[AppScale]]\n* [[Bitnami]]\n* [[CopperEgg]]\n* [[ElasticHosts]]\n* [[Eucalyptus (computing)]]\n* [[FlexiScale]]\n* [[FUJITSU Cloud IaaS Trusted Public S5]]\n* [[GoGrid]]\n* [[Google App Engine]]\n* [[Google Cloud Platform]]\n